\begin_layout Chapter
Quantum State Discrimination 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An integral part of quantum information and quantum processing is measurement
 theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bergou2013"

\end_inset

.
 It is the probabilistic nature of quantum mechanics that one cannot simply
 obtain information encoded in states 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Nielsen2010"

\end_inset

, the state is not an observable in quantum mechanics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Peres1995"

\end_inset

.
 When a quantum circuit or processor has acted on the input states to perform
 a task, the output needs to be read out.
 Thus after the processing occurs the task is to determine the state of
 the system.
 If the input states are orthogonal the process is trivial.
 Simply setting up detectors along the orthogonal directions and a click
 in those detectors will determine the state of the system.
 On the other hand discriminating among non orthogonal quantum states is
 not trivial.
 Since quantum mechanics does not allow for perfect discrimination of non
 orthogonal states the task becomes that of a measurement optimization problem.
 Not being able to perfectly discriminate quantum states is key to various
 quantum cryptographic schemes and quantum computing.
 The origin of the state discrimination field is attributed to the works
 of Helstrom 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Helstrom1969"

\end_inset

 and Holevo 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Holevo2011"

\end_inset

.
 The field however gained momentum in the 90's as quantum information theory
 became very active primarily due to the factorization work of Peter Schor
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shor1994"

\end_inset

 and quantum key distribution protocols such as B92 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bennett1992"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Various optimum state discrimination measurement strategies have been developed
 with respect to some figure of merit.
 Two of those methods which we focus on are optimum Unambiguous Discrimination
 (UD) and Minimum Error (ME).
 In UD strategy, first suggested by Ivanovic 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ivanovic1987"

\end_inset

, the observer Bob, is not allowed to make an error.
 Whenever he is handed a state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 he cannot conclude that he was given 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{j}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 We will show that this cannot be done with 100% success rate and that the
 observer must allow for inconclusive results and find an optimum measurement
 strategy which minimizes the average rate of inconclusive results.
 In the Minimum Error strategy the observer is not allowed to have inconclusive
 results.
 Thus errors are allowed and the task is to find optimum measurements that
 minimize the average error rate.
 It has been shown that ME and UD are special cases of a more general scheme
 of optimum state discrimination measurement which can be approached by
 relaxing the conditions at either end 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chefles1998b"

\end_inset

.
 In the ME scheme the optimal error rate can be further reduced by allowing
 for some rate of inconclusive results.
 Thus the optimal average error rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E},$
\end_inset

 becomes a function of a given rate of allowed inconclusive results 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}(Q)$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, in UD, the optimal rate of the average inconclusive
 outcomes, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q,$
\end_inset

 may be reduced by allowing for some error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}$
\end_inset

.
 The failure rate becomes a function of a given error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(P_{E}).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our work we use various quantum measurements schemes to read out information
 out of a quantum system.
 For a more thorough understanding of quantum theory of measurements we
 go along the lines of the review paper by J.A Bergou 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bergou2010"

\end_inset

.
 Starting with the standard quantum measurement theory due essentially to
 von Neumann the generalized measurements (Positive Operator Valued Measures,
 POVMs) are introduced as more useful measurement schemes in optimization
 problems.
 Using Neumark's theorem the POVMs can be realized experimentally.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Standard Quantum Measurements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with the postulates of standard or projective quantum measurements
 introduced by von Neumann 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Neumann1955"

\end_inset

 analyzing a model for the coupling of the system with the meter or ancilla
 and generalizing the predictions of the model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The postulates are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Observables in quantum mechanics have a Hermintian operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 which has a spectral representation 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=\sum_{j}^{N}\lambda_{j}\ket j\bra j$
\end_inset

, where the eigenvalues are real and assuming non-degeneracy for simplicity.
 The eigenvectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket j\right\} $
\end_inset

 form a complete orthonormal basis set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The Hilbert space is spanned by the projectors 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{j}=\ket j\bra j$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j}P_{j}=1.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The eigenvalues of the projectors are 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 due to the orthogonality of the states 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}P_{j}=P_{i}\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Any measurement of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 will yield one of the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 is obtained in a measurements, the state of the system collapses onto:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phi_{j}}=\frac{P_{j}\ket{\psi}}{\sqrt{\sandwich{\psi}{P_{j}}{\psi}}}$
\end_inset

 if the system was initially in a pure state, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{j}=\frac{P_{j}\rho P_{j}}{Tr(P_{j}\rho)}$
\end_inset

 if the system was initially in a mixed state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The probability of obtaining 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phi_{j}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}=\left|\left|P_{j}\psi\right|\right|^{2}=\sandwich{\psi}{P_{j}^{2}}{\psi}=\sandwich{\psi}{P_{j}}{\psi}$
\end_inset

.
 The probability of obtaining 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{j}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}=Tr(P_{j}\rho P_{j})=Tr(P_{j}^{2}\rho)=Tr(P_{j}\rho)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If a measurement is performed but the result is not recorded the post-measuremen
t state collapses onto: 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\sum_{j}P_{j}\ket{\psi}\bra{\psi}P_{j}$
\end_inset

 if the system was initially in a pure state, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\rho}=\sum_{j}p_{j}\rho_{j}=\sum_{j}P_{j}\rho P_{j}$
\end_inset

 if the system was initially in a mixed state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
POVMs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to the orthogonality condition of the projective measurements one cannot
 have more orthogonal projections than the dimensionality, hence the possible
 outcomes cannot exceed the number of the dimensionality.
 Sometimes we would like to allow for more outcomes than the dimensionality,
 as in the case of optimal UD measurements where we have three outcomes
 in a two dimensional problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next we introduce a positive operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{j}\geq0$
\end_inset

 as a generalization of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{j}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and the probability of obtaining state 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}=Tr(\Pi_{j}\rho_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 To normalize the probabilities we require that the positive operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{j}$
\end_inset

 are a decomposition of the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j}\Pi_{j}=I$
\end_inset

.
 This is decomposition is called a Positive Operator Valued Measure (POVM)
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{j}$
\end_inset

 the elements of the POVM.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The generalization of the postulates of quantum mechanics in terms of the
 POVM can be expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The decomposition of the identity in terms of positive operators, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{j}\geq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j}\Pi_{j}=I$
\end_inset

 is called a POVM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The elements of the POVM can be expressed in terms of the detection operators
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{j}=A_{j}^{\dagger}A_{j}$
\end_inset

 where the operators satisfy the requirements 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j}A_{j}^{\dagger}A_{j}=I$
\end_inset

 but they need not be Hermitian.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A detection yields an element on POVM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The state of the system collapses onto: 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phi_{j}}=\frac{A_{j}\ket{\psi}}{\sqrt{\sandwich{\psi}{A_{j}^{\dagger}A_{j}}{\psi}}}$
\end_inset

 if the system was initially in a pure state, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{j}=\frac{A_{j}^{\dagger}\rho A_{j}}{Tr(A_{j}\rho A_{j}^{\dagger})}=\frac{A_{j}^{\dagger}\rho A_{j}}{Tr(A_{j}^{\dagger}A_{j}\rho)}=\frac{A_{j}^{\dagger}\rho A_{j}}{Tr(\Pi_{j}\rho)}$
\end_inset

 if the system was initially in a mixed state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The probability of obtaining 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{j}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}=Tr(A_{j}\rho_{j}A_{j}^{\dagger})=Tr(A_{j}^{\dagger}A_{j}\rho_{j})=Tr(\Pi_{j}\rho_{j})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If a measurement is performed but the result is not recorded the post-measuremen
t state collapses onto: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\rho}=\sum_{j}p_{j}\rho_{j}=\sum_{j}A_{j}\rho A_{j}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is these generalized measurements we will use in our optimization work.
 In the following sections POVM elements are used to optimize the unambiguous
 discrimination and minimum error schemes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Unambiguous Discrimination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we give a review of the existing schemes of Unambiguous
 Discrimination (UD).
 Particularly that of two pure states as it is directly related with our
 work.
 When performing UD the detectors are not allowed to make an error but can
 admit inconclusive outcomes.
 We first show by contradiction that it is not possible to succeed at unambiguou
sly discriminating quantum states with 100% success rate.
 Then we show that in order to perform UD a third detector must be added
 which accounts for inconclusive results.
 The task is to minimize this rate of inconclusive outcomes.
 In Subsection (1.1.1) the problem is solved via the POVM strategy.
 In the following Subsection (1.1.2) we show how the solution can be implemented
 via the Neumark theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Unambiguous Discrimination: Two pure states via POVM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An ensemble of quantum states is prepared with two possible pure states
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 Each state is prepared with an a priori probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}=1.$
\end_inset

 The observer has full knowledge of the states and their priors.
 The preparer, Alice, picks up a state and hands it over to the observer,
 Bob.
 Bob's task it to determine which state he is given by performing a single
 a POVM on the individual system he is given.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As it was stated earlier, the observer is not allowed to make an error when
 performing a measurement.
 Let us assume Bob can indeed discriminate the given states with 100% success
 rate.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}$
\end_inset

 be detectors which cover the full Hilbert space spanned by the states 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2}=I\label{eq:2POVM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the UD strategy the detector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 identifies only the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and never clicks for 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{j}\rangle,$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}|\psi_{j}\rangle=0.$
\end_inset

 Multiplying Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2POVM"

\end_inset

) by 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 from the right and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\psi_{1}|$
\end_inset

 from the left results in 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=\langle\psi_{1}|\Pi_{1}|\psi_{1}\rangle=1$
\end_inset

, which is the probability of successfully identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{|\psi_{1}\rangle}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly it can be shown that the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 can be detected with a probability one, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}=\langle\psi_{2}|\Pi_{2}|\psi_{2}\rangle=1.$
\end_inset

 Seems as if one can indeed discriminate two non-orthogonal quantum states
 with a 100% success rate.
 However multiplying 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
Equation.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2POVM"

\end_inset

)
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\psi_{1}|$
\end_inset

 from the left and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 from the right it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle=0,$
\end_inset

 where we use 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}|\psi_{j}\rangle=0.$
\end_inset

 This means that the input states are orthogonal to begin with, which is
 a contradiction because we started with nonorthogonal quantum states.
 Thus one cannot discriminate non-orthogonal quantum state with 100% success
 rate (orthogonal states can indeed be discriminated with no error rate,
 they correspond to classical states).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can still perform Unambiguous Discrimination but with a modified scheme.
 Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2POVM"

\end_inset

) is modified by adding a third detector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 which can click for both states 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle:$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2}+\Pi_{0}=I\label{eq:3povms}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The clicks from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 are all inconclusive, i.e we gain no information from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}.$
\end_inset

 Defining individual failure rates 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=\langle\psi_{1}|\Pi_{0}|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}=\langle\psi_{2}|\Pi_{0}|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 as the failure probabilities, the task becomes that of minimizing the overall
 failure rate, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}.\label{eq:Q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equivalently optimizing the success rate 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{E}=\eta_{1}p_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2},
\]

\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}+Q=1.$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now explicitly determine the POVM operators to be used in the optimizatio
n of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, see Figure (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD"

\end_inset

).
 First define the states to be in a two dimensional plane, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
|\psi_{1}\rangle & = & \cos\theta|0\rangle+\sin\theta|1\rangle,\\
|\psi_{2}\rangle & = & \cos\theta|0\rangle-\sin\theta|1\rangle.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The detectors must be orthogonal with the states for which they should not
 identify, i.e 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}|\psi_{j}\rangle=0$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Pi_{1} & = & c_{1}|\psi_{2}^{\perp}\rangle\langle\psi_{2}^{\perp}|,\\
\Pi_{2} & = & c_{2}|\psi_{1}^{\perp}\rangle\langle\psi_{1}^{\perp}|,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}^{\perp}\rangle=\sin\theta|0\rangle+\cos\theta|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}^{\perp}\rangle=-\sin\theta|0\rangle+\cos\theta|1\rangle$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

 are yet to be determined based on the optimum strategies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the definition of success probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=\langle\psi_{i}|\Pi_{i}|\psi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be replaced, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Pi_{1} & = & \frac{p_{1}}{|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}^{\perp}\rangle|^{2}}|\psi_{2}^{\perp}\rangle\langle\psi_{2}^{\perp}|,\nonumber \\
\Pi_{2} & = & \frac{p_{2}}{|\langle\psi_{2}|\psi_{1}^{\perp}\rangle|^{2}}|\psi_{1}^{\perp}\rangle\langle\psi_{1}^{\perp}|.\label{eq:Pi1Pi2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename UD.pdf
	width 8.5cm
	height 8.5cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space \hspace{}
\length 1cm
\end_inset

UD Detectors
\end_layout

\end_inset

 POVM setup that unambiguously discriminates between 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 optimally.
 The detector 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}=\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is setup along 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}^{\perp}}$
\end_inset

, detector 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}=\Pi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is setup along 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}^{\perp}}$
\end_inset

 and the failure operator is setup symmetrically between 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 When a click in the 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{i}$
\end_inset

 detector occurs we know for certain that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{i}}$
\end_inset

 was prepared 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(i=1,2\right)$
\end_inset

 as the input state since it is the only one that has a component along
 this direction.
 A click in the 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{0}$
\end_inset

 detector is considered inconclusive as both states have a component along
 this direction
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "UD"

\end_inset

 direction
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To determine the failure operator, insert (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Pi1Pi2"

\end_inset

) into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3povms"

\end_inset

): 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{0}=I-\Pi_{1}-\Pi_{2}=I-\frac{p_{1}}{|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}^{\perp}\rangle|^{2}}|\psi_{2}^{\perp}\rangle\langle\psi_{2}^{\perp}|-\frac{p_{2}}{|\langle\psi_{2}|\psi_{1}^{\perp}\rangle|^{2}}|\psi_{1}^{\perp}\rangle\langle\psi_{1}^{\perp}|.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After writing everything explicitly, the positivity constraint of the eigenvalue
s of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 gives the condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{1}q_{2}\geq|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{2},\label{eq:qConstraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where we used 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}=1-p_{i}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the condition (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:qConstraint"

\end_inset

) and taking the equality sign, the total failure rate in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Q"

\end_inset

) can be expressed in terms of a single constraint.
 Define the overlap 
\begin_inset Formula $s\equiv\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=s^{2}/q_{2}$
\end_inset

 into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Q"

\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\frac{\eta_{1}s^{2}}{q_{2}}+\eta_{2}q_{2},$
\end_inset

 the optimization follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\frac{\partial Q}{\partial q_{2}}=-\frac{\eta_{1}s^{2}}{q_{2}^{2}}+\eta_{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This leads to individual failure rates 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{\eta_{2}}{\eta_{1}}}s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}=\sqrt{\frac{\eta_{1}}{\eta_{2}}}s$
\end_inset

 .
 Inserting them back into Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Q"

\end_inset

) gives the optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 which it will be defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{0}=2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now check the conditions where this result holds.
 The individual error rates must be smaller or equal to one, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}\leq1.$
\end_inset

 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{1-\eta_{1}}{\eta_{1}}}s\leq1$
\end_inset

 gives the lower bound on the a-prior probabilities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\geq\frac{s^{2}}{1+s^{2}}.$
\end_inset

 Similarly the condition that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}\leq1$
\end_inset

 gives the upper bound on the priors 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\leq\frac{1}{1+s^{2}}.$
\end_inset

 Putting the two conditions together the POVM regime is valid in the range:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{s^{2}}{1+s^{2}}\leq\eta_{1}\leq\frac{1}{1+s^{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Outside of this range it is interesting to see that the measurement strategy
 merges into the projective measurement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If one of the incoming states is prepared with a much higher probability,
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\gg\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, we design an experiment where we have only two detection operators.
 One of them, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{0}$
\end_inset

, the failure operator, simply projects onto state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle,$
\end_inset

 the detector 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 projects onto 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}^{\perp}\rangle,$
\end_inset

 thus it never clicks for 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle,$
\end_inset

 so that a click on 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 is associated with the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 A click along 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

 is failure.
 The setup for the detectors which produce failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}$
\end_inset

 is shown in Figure (1.1.2).
 The total failure rate is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{1}=\eta_{1}|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{2}+\eta_{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Q_1.jpg
	width 10cm
	height 10cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space \hspace{}
\length 1cm
\end_inset

von Neumann UD for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 A von Neumann measurement that discriminates 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 unambiguously.
 The failure detector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}=P_{2}$
\end_inset

 is set up along the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 direction and the second detector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}=P_{2}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 is set up orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 therefore never clicks for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}.$
\end_inset

 When a click in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 detector occurs we learn nothing as both states have an overlap along 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Q_1"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}\gg\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

, the corresponding setup with detectors yielding 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{2}$
\end_inset

 is shown in Figure (1.1.3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{2}=\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Q_2.jpg
	width 10cm
	height 10cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space \hspace{}
\length 1cm
\end_inset

von Neumann UD for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 A von Neumann measurement that discriminates 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 unambiguously.
 The failure detector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}=P_{1}$
\end_inset

 is set up along the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 direction and the second detector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}=P_{1}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 is set up orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 therefore never clicks for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}.$
\end_inset

 When a click in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 detector occurs, we learn nothing as both states have an overlap along
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Q_2"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Putting the pieces together, the minimum value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 for the three different regimes can be written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=\begin{cases}
2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s & \text{if }\frac{s^{2}}{1+s^{2}}\leq\eta_{1}\leq\frac{1}{1+s^{2}},\\
\eta_{1}|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{2}+\eta_{2}\text{ if } & \eta_{1}>\frac{1}{1+s^{2}},\\
\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{2}\text{ if } & \eta_{1}<\frac{s^{2}}{1+s^{2}}.
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is very interesting that the POVM gives the minimum 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 when it is valid.
 Outside the boundaries it merges with the von Neumann projective measurement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Unambiguous Discrimination: Two pure states via Neumark's Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Theoretically the problem of minimizing the average failure rate for two
 pure states has been solved in the previous section.
 However to be able to implement those schemes we resort to Neumark's theorem
 which states that any POVM operator can be realized by generalized measurements
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cite-keyneumark"

\end_inset

.
 The system where the incoming states live is embedded in a larger Hilbert
 space called ancilla.
 Then a unitary operator entangles the degrees of freedom of the system
 with those of the ancilla.
 After this interaction projective measurements are performed within this
 larger system in the ancilla.
 These measurements will also transform the system states in the original
 Hilbert space because of the entanglement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To show the power of Neumark's theorem we will re-derive the optimal failure
 rate of two nonorthogonal states.
 The incoming states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s},|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}\}$
\end_inset

 which live in the state Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{S}$
\end_inset

 are embedded with the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|i\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 which live in the ancilla Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{A}.$
\end_inset

 Now the system and the ancilla live in the larger Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H=H_{S}\varotimes H_{A}.$
\end_inset

 The incoming states in this larger Hilbert space can be written in the
 product form 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a},\ |\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a}\},$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket i_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the initial state of the ancilla.
 The unitary operator does the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a} & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\psi'_{1}\rangle_{s}|1\rangle_{a}+\sqrt{q_{1}}|\phi\rangle_{s}|0\rangle_{a},\nonumber \\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a} & = & \sqrt{p_{2}}|\psi'_{2}\rangle_{s}|2\rangle_{a}+\sqrt{q_{2}}|\phi\rangle_{s}|0\rangle_{a},\label{eq:neumark}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of successfully identifying the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle_{s}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of failing to identify 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle_{s},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}+q_{i}=1.$
\end_inset

 The unitary operator aims to take the two incoming states and make them
 orthogonal.
 When there is a click on the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 the input states have been separated and output states 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi'_{i}\rangle_{s}$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal and therefore fully distinguishable.
 If there is a click along the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 the incoming states have been collapsed into a single state which carries
 no information about the system.
 That is why the choice on the setup of having the failed state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\phi\rangle_{s}$
\end_inset

 be the same, there should be absolutely no information left in the failed
 state, otherwise it is not optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the inner product of the two equations in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:neumark"

\end_inset

) gives the constraint to the optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 was defined to be the overlap of the input states 
\begin_inset Formula $s\equiv\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 In just one line Neumark's setup has produced the constrain and the rest
 of the derivation, optimizing (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Q"

\end_inset

), is the same as in the POVM section and we do not need to repeat here.
 Implementation methods have been derived and we will show an example in
 Chapter 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Minimum Error Discrimination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Minimum Error (ME) strategy one is not allowed to abstain from identifyin
g an incoming state, i.e for every incoming state the observer must say which
 state he was given.
 Since it was shown that perfect discrimination is not possible the detectors
 inevitably will make errors.
 A click in a detector can only identify a state with some probability of
 success and misidentify the state with some probability of error.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Minimum Error: Two mixed states via POVM 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given an ensemble of two mixed states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{1},\rho_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 prepared with different a priori probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\eta_{1},\eta_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 the task is to minimize the rate for which the detectors misidentify a
 state.
 The minimum error problem for two pure or mixed states was first solved
 by Helstrom 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Helstrom1969"

\end_inset

.
 We show an alternative derivation to ME of two pure states developed by
 Herzog 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Herzog2004"

\end_inset

 and Fuchs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fuchs1996"

\end_inset

.
 When the detector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 clicks for state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{j}$
\end_inset

 it is an error, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}=Tr(\rho_{j}\Pi_{i})$
\end_inset

, a clink for state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

 is success 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=Tr(\rho_{i}\Pi_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus for two states we want to minimize the following expression.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\eta_{1}Tr(\rho_{1}\Pi_{2})+\eta_{2}Tr(\rho_{2}\Pi_{1}).\label{eq:P_E}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2}=I$
\end_inset

, Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:P_E"

\end_inset

) can be rewritten as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{E} & = & \eta_{1}Tr(\rho_{1}(I-\Pi_{1}))+\eta_{2}Tr(\rho_{2}\Pi_{1}),\\
 & = & \eta_{1}+Tr[(\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1})\Pi_{1},\\
 & = & \eta_{2}-Tr[(\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1})\Pi_{2}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda=\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\eta_{1}+Tr(\Lambda\Pi_{1})=\eta_{2}-Tr(\Lambda\Pi_{2}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To minimize 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 should project onto the eigenvectors of the negative eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda,$
\end_inset

 on the other hand 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}$
\end_inset

 should project onto the positive eigenvectors.
 Let us write 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 into its spectral decomposition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda=\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1}=\sum_{i=1}^{d}\lambda_{i}|\lambda_{i}\rangle\langle\lambda_{i}|.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To implement the projection of the POVM operators onto the positive (or
 negative) eigenvectors the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be split into three categories without any loss of generality: negative,
 positive and zero:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\lambda_{i} & < & 0\text{ for }1\leq i<i_{o},\nonumber \\
\lambda_{i} & > & 0\text{ for \ensuremath{i_{o}\leq i<d}},\nonumber \\
\lambda_{i} & = & 0\text{ for \ensuremath{d\leq i<d_{s}}. }
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then from the spectral decomposition we can rewrite 
\begin_inset Formula $(2.2.6)$
\end_inset

 in terms of the optimal POVM.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\eta_{1}+\sum_{i=1}^{i_{o}-1}\lambda_{i}\langle\lambda_{i}|\Pi_{1}|\lambda_{i}\rangle=\eta_{2}-\sum_{i=i_{o}}^{d_{s}}\lambda_{i}\langle\lambda_{i}|\Pi_{2}|\lambda_{i}\rangle,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}=\sum_{i=1}^{i_{o}-1}\lambda_{i}|\lambda_{i}\rangle\langle\lambda_{i}|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}=\sum_{i=i_{o}}^{d_{s}}\lambda_{i}|\lambda_{i}\rangle\langle\lambda_{i}|.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The POVMs need to satisfy the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\langle\lambda_{i}|\Pi_{j}|\lambda_{i}\rangle\leq1$
\end_inset

 which comes from the definition of the normalized probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}=Tr(\rho_{i}\Pi_{j}).$
\end_inset

 These POVMs are basically von Neumann projectors onto the corresponding
 eigenvectors.
 If we now replace the detection operators by the optimal detectors the
 minimum error can be expressed just in terms of the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{E} & = & \eta_{1}-\sum_{i=1}^{i_{o}-1}|\lambda_{i}|=\eta_{2}-\sum_{i=1}^{d_{s}}|\lambda_{i}|,\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-\sum_{i=1}^{d_{s}}|\lambda_{i}|]=\frac{1}{2}[1-Tr|\Lambda|],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-Tr|\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1}|]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the states to be discriminated are pure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\},$
\end_inset

 the minimum error can be reduced to 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}[1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{2}}].
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ME.pdf
	width 8.5cm
	height 8.5cm

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space \hspace{}
\length 1cm
\end_inset

Min Error
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A von Neumann measurement which minimizes the error rate of two pure states
 prepared with equal priors.
 The detectors are placed symmetrically along the states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}},\ket{\psi_{2}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "POVM_ME"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Minimum Error: Two pure states via Neumark's theorem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as we did in the UD case, we will solve the ME problem of discriminating
 two pure states via the Neumark setup because of it lends itself into an
 optical implementation.
 Although in this case the solution is not as straightforward.
 The incoming states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s},|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}\}$
\end_inset

 which live in the state Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{S}$
\end_inset

 are embedded with the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|i\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 which live in the ancilla Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{A}.$
\end_inset

 Now the system and the ancilla live in the larger Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H=H_{S}\varotimes H_{A}.$
\end_inset

 The incoming states in this larger Hilbert space can be written in the
 product form 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a},\ |\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a}\}.$
\end_inset

 The unitary operator does the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a} & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\psi_{1}\rangle|1\rangle+\sqrt{r_{1}}|\psi_{2}\rangle|2\rangle,\\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a} & = & \sqrt{p_{2}}|\psi_{2}\rangle|2\rangle+\sqrt{r_{2}}|\psi_{1}\rangle|1\rangle,\label{eq:ME neumark}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of having successfully identified the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of misidentifying the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the inner product of the two equations in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ME neumark"

\end_inset

) gives the constraint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}+\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}.\label{eq:ME constraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The quantity we are looking to minimize in the average error rate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2},\label{eq:ME}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 subject to the constraint in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ME constraint"

\end_inset

).
 Adding the constraint to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ME"

\end_inset

 with one Lagrange multiplier and using 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}+r_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}+\lambda\left[s-\sqrt{(1-r_{1})r_{2}}-\sqrt{(1-r_{2})r_{1}}\right].
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Differentiating with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

, then setting the resulting equations equal to zero yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial F_{E}}{\partial r_{1}}=\eta_{1}+\frac{1}{2}\left[\sqrt{\frac{r_{2}}{1-r_{1}}}-\sqrt{\frac{1-r_{2}}{r_{1}}}\right]=0,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial F_{E}}{\partial r_{2}}=\eta_{2}+\frac{1}{2}\left[-\sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-r_{2}}}+\sqrt{\frac{1-r_{1}}{r_{2}}}\right]=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rearranging the above two equations so that the left hand side is only a
 function of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the right hand sides turn out to be equivalent, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{2\eta_{1}}{\lambda}\sqrt{r_{1}(1-r_{1})}=\sqrt{r_{1}r_{2}}-\sqrt{(1-r_{1})(1-r_{2})},\label{eq:r12}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{2\eta_{2}}{\lambda}\sqrt{r_{2}(1-r_{2})}=\sqrt{r_{1}r_{2}}-\sqrt{(1-r_{1})(1-r_{2})}.\label{eq:r1r2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The right hand sides of Eq.(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r12"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r1r2"

\end_inset

) can be set to a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\eta_{i}}{\lambda}\sqrt{r_{i}(1-r_{i})}\equiv C$
\end_inset

, which can later be determined from the unitarity constraint 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ME constraint"

\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{i} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left(1\pm\sqrt{1-\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}}}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(1-\sqrt{1-\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}}}\right),\label{eq:r_i-1}\\
r_{i} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1-A_{i}\right],
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}\equiv\sqrt{1-\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{2}\equiv\lambda^{2}C^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is picked (lower sign in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r_i-1"

\end_inset

 ) as this represents error rate, which is to be minimized.
 Now replace 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 into the constraint (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ME constraint"

\end_inset

) and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
s & = & \sqrt{(1-r_{1})r_{2}}+\sqrt{(1-r_{2})r_{1}},\\
2s & = & \sqrt{(1+A_{1})(1-A_{2})}+\sqrt{(1-A_{1})(1+A_{2})},\\
2s^{2} & = & 1-A_{1}A_{2}+\sqrt{(1-A_{1}^{2})(1-A_{2}^{2})},\\
2s^{2} & = & 1-A_{1}A_{2}+\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}},\\
(2s^{2}-1 & -\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}})^{2}= & 1-\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{1}^{2}}-\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{2}^{2}}+\frac{\delta^{4}}{\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After some tedious but trivial algebra:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta^{2}=\frac{4s^{2}(1-s^{2})\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}.\label{eq:delta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now substitute the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta"

\end_inset

) into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r_i-1"

\end_inset

) to get the explicit form of the individual error rates,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r_{i}=\frac{1}{2}\left[1-\frac{1-2\eta_{i}s^{2}}{\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inserting 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:P_E"

\end_inset

) Helstrom bound is retrieved 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Helstrom1969"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{E} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1-\frac{\eta_{1}-2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}{\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}}-\frac{\eta_{2}-2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}{\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}}\right],\nonumber \\
P_{E} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}\right].
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we mentioned above the advantage of solving the ME problem via Neumark
 is that we now have explicit expressions for the individual error rates,
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}.$
\end_inset

 In the Implementation chapter, it is shown that the unitary operator which
 carries out this operation can be written in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and then be decomposed into beam splitters and phase shifters using optical
 interferometers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Optimal discrimination of a certain class of mixed states with a fixed rate
 of inconclusive outcome (FRIO)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter we will derive the optimal strategy with a Fixed Rate of
 Inconclusive Outcomes (
\begin_inset Formula $FRIO$
\end_inset

) that optimally interpolates between the two well known limits, Helstrom
 bound for minimum error and IDP for unambiguous discrimination.
 In particular, as the main finding of our paper, we will show that the
 optimal distribution of the fixed rate of inconclusive outcomes, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, among the 2-dimensional subspaces spanned by the pair of Jordan basis
 vectors is highly non-trivial and an interesting threshold-like structure
 emerges: As we start increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

 , first only one subspace receives the entire inconclusive rate.
 Then, as we increase 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 further, at a certain threshold a second subspace starts sharing the inconclusi
ve rate.
 If we increase 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 further, at another threshold a third subspace also starts sharing 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 , and so on, until above a last threshold all subspaces share the available
 inconclusive rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Review of the FRIO solution for two pure states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first present a brief review of the method developed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan2012"

\end_inset

 for the two pure state optimal FRIO problem since the rest of the paper
 relies heavily on this method.
 We derive the maximum probability of success or, equivalently, the minimum
 probability of error in identifying the states, when a certain fixed rate
 of inconclusive outcomes is allowed.
 By varying the inconclusive rate, the scheme optimally interpolates between
 Unambiguous and Minimum Error discrimination (UD and ME).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all of these scenarios (UD, ME or FRIO) one is given a system which is
 promised to be prepared in one of two known pure states, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, but we don't know which.
 The pure states are prepared with prior probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, respectively, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 It is well known that two pure states can be discriminated both unambiguously
 and with minimum error.
 In Section (2.1) we showed the solution of the optimal average inconclusive
 rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 for UD:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{{\rm c}}=\left\{ \begin{array}{l}
\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}\cos^{2}\theta,\mbox{if \ensuremath{{\displaystyle \eta_{1}<\frac{\cos^{2}\theta}{1+\cos^{2}\theta}\equiv\eta_{1}^{(l)}}},}\\[0.7em]
\eta_{2}+\eta_{1}\cos^{2}\theta,\mbox{if \ensuremath{\eta_{1}>{\displaystyle \frac{1}{1+\cos^{2}\theta}\equiv\eta_{1}^{(r)}}},}\\[0.7em]
2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}\cos\theta\equiv Q_{0},\mbox{if \ensuremath{\eta_{1}^{(l)}\le\eta_{1}\le\eta_{1}^{(r)}}}\ ,
\end{array}\right.\label{Qmax}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|\equiv\cos\theta$
\end_inset

 is the overlap of the input states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Section (2.2) we also showed the optimal average error rate for ME: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{{\rm E}}^{ME}=\frac{1}{2}\left(1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\cos^{2}\theta}\;\right).\label{PE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has long been suggested 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chefles1998"

\end_inset

 that the above state discrimination points are part of a more general scheme.
 One which interpolates between optimal ME and UD.
 The FRIO strategy achieves that goal by minimizing the error rate while
 allowing for some rate of inconclusive results.
 Hence the strategy has three measurement outcomes, one that identifies
 with the first state, one that identifies with the second state and one
 that does not identify with a state at all, corresponding to the inconclusive
 outcome.
 The authors in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan2012"

\end_inset

 solve the problem via the POVM method.
 Three POVM elements are needed such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2}+\Pi_{0}=I\ ,\label{POVM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A click in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is identified with state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}},$
\end_inset

 a click in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is identified with the second state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 and any clicks in the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to inconclusive outcomes.
 However the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 can also click for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{j}}.$
\end_inset

 We wish to minimize the average error rate,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{E} & = & \eta_{1}Tr\left[\sandwich{\psi_{1}}{\Pi_{2}}{\psi_{1}}\right]+\eta_{2}Tr\left[\sandwich{\psi_{2}}{\Pi_{1}}{\psi_{2}}\right],\\
 & = & \eta_{1}tr\left[\Pi_{2}\ket{\psi_{1}}\bra{\psi_{1}}\right]+\eta_{2}tr\left[\Pi_{1}\ket{\psi_{2}}\bra{\psi_{2}}\right],\\
 & = & \eta_{1}tr\left[\Pi_{2}\rho_{1}\right]+\eta_{2}tr\left[\Pi_{1}\rho_{2}\right],
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}=\ket{\psi_{1}}\bra{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}=\ket{\psi_{2}}\bra{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 are the corresponding pure state density matrices (Equivalently we wish
 to maximize the average success rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}=\eta_{1}tr\left[\Pi_{1}\rho_{1}\right]+\eta_{2}tr\left[\Pi_{2}\rho_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

), for a fixed rate of inconclusive results,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=\eta_{1}tr\left[\Pi_{0}\rho_{1}\right]+\eta_{2}tr\left[\Pi_{0}\rho_{2}\right]\ .\label{Q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution to the problem involves a neat trick which transforms the three
 element POVM defined in Eq.(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "POVM"

\end_inset

) into a two element POVM, namely,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2} & = & I-\Pi_{0},\nonumber \\
\Omega^{-1/2}\left(\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2}\right)\Omega^{-1/2} & = & \Omega^{-1/2}\left(I-\Pi_{0}\right)\Omega^{-1/2},\nonumber \\
\tilde{\Pi}_{1}+\tilde{\Pi}_{2} & = & I,
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\equiv I-\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Pi}_{i}\equiv\Omega^{-1/2}\Pi_{i}\,\Omega^{-1/2}.$
\end_inset

 Should be noted that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-1/2}=\left(I-\Pi_{0}\right)^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 exists unless 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 has a unit value, in which case the problem is treated separately.
 It was important to notice that for optimal FRIO, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 must be rank one operator.
 That means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 maps both incoming non-orthogonal states onto a single state which is then
 discarded.
 On the other hand the other two POVM elements map the input states onto
 two different states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The FRIO problem has essentially been transformed into a new parametrized
 optimization scheme with two POVM elements, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Pi}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Pi}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The error probability in the new parametrized form, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=(1-Q)\tilde{P}_{E}$
\end_inset

, becomes 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\tilde{P}_{e} & = & Tr(\tilde{\eta}_{1}\tilde{\rho}_{1}\tilde{\Pi}_{2})+Tr(\tilde{\eta}_{2}\tilde{\rho}_{2}\tilde{\Pi}_{1}),\label{tildePe}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the normalized states 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\rho}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and normalized a priori probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\eta}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\rho}_{i}=\frac{\Omega^{1/2}\rho_{i}\Omega^{1/2}}{Tr(\Omega\rho_{i}))},\qquad\tilde{\eta}_{i}=\frac{\eta_{i}Tr(\Omega\rho_{i})}{1-Q},\label{tildestates}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "tildePe"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Pi}_{1}+\tilde{\Pi}_{2}=I$
\end_inset

 define a ME discrimination problem for the transformed states and 
\emph on
priors
\emph default
 given in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "tildestates"

\end_inset

.
 The optimal solution to this ME discrimination problem immediately follows
 by using the tilde quantities in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PE"

\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $|\tilde{\psi}_{i}\rangle=\Omega^{1/2}|\psi_{i}\rangle/\sqrt{\langle\psi_{i}|\Omega|\psi_{i}\rangle}$
\end_inset

 being the properly normalized transformed states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can immediately write down the solution in parametrized form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{P}_{{\rm E}}^{ME}=\frac{1}{2}\left(1-\sqrt{1-4\tilde{\eta}_{1}\tilde{\eta}_{2}\left|\braket{\tilde{\psi}_{1}}{\tilde{\psi}_{2}}\right|^{2}}\;\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Writing the input states as, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle=c_{i}|0\rangle+s_{i}|1\rangle$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\equiv\cos\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\equiv\sin\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the transformed states and priors from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "tildestates"

\end_inset

.
 Since the optimal
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a positive rank one operator it can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}=\xi|0\rangle\langle0|$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is its eigenvalue, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\xi\leq1$
\end_inset

, and the eigenstate belonging to 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle$
\end_inset

 and the orthogonal state is 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 In this basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=(1-\xi)|0\rangle\langle0|+|1\rangle\langle1|$
\end_inset

.
 The tilde error rate now becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If enough time show more steps to this derivation, look up your notes for
 more details.
 They should be in the office typed up.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{P}_{e}^{{\rm ME}}=\frac{1}{2}\left\{ 1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(\cos\theta-\xi c_{1}c_{2})^{2}/(1-Q)^{2}}\right\} ,\label{tildePe3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\equiv\theta$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Q"

\end_inset

) that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\xi=\frac{Q}{\eta_{1}c_{1}^{2}+\eta_{2}c_{2}^{2}}.\label{xi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "tildePe3"

\end_inset

 depends only on one parameter, say
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

, which determines the orientation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 relative to that of the two pure states.
 The minimization over 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

 simplifies considerably, using Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "xi"

\end_inset

) and defining 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}\,\eta_{1}^{1/2}(\eta_{1}c_{1}^{2}+\eta_{2}c_{2}^{2})^{-1/2}\equiv\cos\varphi$
\end_inset

, and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}\,\eta_{2}^{1/2}(\eta_{1}c_{1}^{2}+\eta_{2}c_{2}^{2})^{-1/2}\equiv\sin\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting expression is minimum for
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\pi/4$
\end_inset

, yielding 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{e}^{{\rm min}}\!=\!\frac{1}{2}\!\left\{ 1-Q-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-\left(Q_{0}-Q\right)^{2}}\right\} \ ,\label{PeSol1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\leq Q_{0}\equiv2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s$
\end_inset

.
 This is the optimal error rate for an intermediate range of the prior probabili
ties, a rather nice looking formula for a somewhat complicated problem.
 We can check that is reproduces the Helstrom bound for zero failure rate
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}\left[1-\sqrt{1-Q_{0}^{2}}\right]=\frac{1}{2}\left[1-\sqrt{1-2\eta_{2}\eta_{2}s^{2}}\right]$
\end_inset

 and the IDP bound for zero error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $0=\frac{1}{2}\!\left\{ 1-Q-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-\left(Q_{0}-Q\right)^{2}}\right\} \Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{0}\equiv2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the validity of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PeSol1"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\le1$
\end_inset

 must hold.
 The definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\varphi$
\end_inset

 after Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "xi"

\end_inset

) give 
\begin_inset Formula ${\sqrt{\eta}_{2}c_{2}=\sqrt{\eta}_{1}c_{1}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\pi/4$
\end_inset

 which, in turn, leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}c_{1}^{2}=\eta_{2}c_{2}^{2}=\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\,{\sin^{2}\theta/(1-Q_{0})}$
\end_inset

, and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "xi"

\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=(1-Q_{0})Q/(2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin^{2}\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=1$
\end_inset

 defines the boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{b}$
\end_inset

, between the projective and POVM regimes, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{{\rm b}}\equiv{2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin^{2}\theta/(1-Q_{0})}.\label{Qb}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\xi\leq1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\leq Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $Q>Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Fig1"

\end_inset

 we plot 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

 vs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 together for a fixed overlap, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta=0.5$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\pi/3$
\end_inset

).
 The two curves intersect at 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{1}^{(l)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{1}^{(r)}$
\end_inset

, the same points as in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qmax"

\end_inset

.
 The interval 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\eta_{1}\leq1$
\end_inset

 is thus divided into three regions.
 In regions
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

I and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

III, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm b}}<Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 and the solution
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PeSol1"

\end_inset

 is valid for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq Q<Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

 only.
 In Region II, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}^{(l)}\leq\eta_{1}\leq\eta_{1}^{(r)}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm c}}=Q_{0}<Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

 and the solution 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PeSol1"

\end_inset

 is valid for the entire 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq Q\leq Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 range.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%[floatfix]
\end_layout

\end_inset


