}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space \hspace{}
\length 1cm
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

 vs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 (dashed line, Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qmax"

\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

 (solid line, Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qb"

\end_inset

) vs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\pi/3$
\end_inset

.
 Measurements can be optimized in the area under the dashed line, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Measurements in the area above 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{c}$
\end_inset

 are suboptimal.
 In the shaded areas between 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{b}$
\end_inset

 (regions I, left, and III, right) the optimal FRIO measurement is a projective
 measurement, in the unshaded area below 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{c}$
\end_inset

 (region II) the optimal measurement is a POVM.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Fig1"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the shaded parts of regions I and III one has 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm b}}\leq Q\leq Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 and, necessarily, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=1$
\end_inset

.
 Hence,
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}=|0\rangle\langle0|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=|1\rangle\langle1|$
\end_inset

 are projectors.
 Therefore,
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 does not exist in these areas and the case needs special consideration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The calculation of the error probability is most easily performed by realizing
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}$
\end_inset

 become degenerate, both must be proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{d}=|1\rangle\langle1|$
\end_inset

.
 The three-element POVM becomes a standard two element projective measurement,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Pi_{d}=|1\rangle\langle1|,\ \Pi_{0}=|0\rangle\langle0|\}$
\end_inset

.
 We identify a click in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{d}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}$
\end_inset

) if 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\ge\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}\ge\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

), so 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e(s)}=\eta_{2}s_{2}^{2},\quad P_{s(e)}=\eta_{1}s_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=1-P_{e}-P_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 These equations completely determine the solution.
 There is nothing to optimize here, so we drop the superscript 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm min}$
\end_inset

 in what follows.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}=\theta$
\end_inset

 immediately gives 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(P_{e})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q\!=\!1\!-\!P_{e}\!-\eta_{1(2)}\!\!\left(\!\sqrt{\!\frac{P_{e}}{\eta_{2(1)}}}\cos\theta\!\pm\!\sqrt{1\!-\!\frac{P_{e}}{\eta_{2(1)}}}\,\sin\theta\!\right)^{\!2}\!.\label{PeSol2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Inverting this equation gives 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}(Q)$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{e}=\eta_{2}\frac{2\eta_{1}\cos^{2}\theta(1-Q-Q_{2})-(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})(Q-Q_{2})-2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin\theta\cos\theta\sqrt{Q(1-Q)-\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin^{2}\theta}}{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\ ,\label{PeSol2Exp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 but the resulting expression is not particularly insightful.
 However, we note that for 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}=0$
\end_inset

 (UD limit) one has
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{2}$
\end_inset

, given by the second line in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Qmax"

\end_inset

), and for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

 reduces to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PeSol1"

\end_inset

, as it should.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
FRIO discrimination of two Rank 2 mixed states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our work we extend the FRIO discrimination scheme to a particular case
 of mixed states.
 We solve the FRIO problem for two mixed states which exhibit a Jordan structure.
 The two states, with their respective 
\emph on
prior
\emph default
 probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, can be written in the spectral decomposition form as, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\rho_{1} & = & \sum_{i=1}^{N}r_{i}\vert r_{i}\rangle\langle r_{i}\vert,\nonumber \\
\rho_{2} & = & \sum_{i=1}^{N}s_{i}\vert s_{i}\rangle\langle s_{i}\vert\ .\label{rho1and2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Jordan structure these states satisfy the following conditions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\langle r_{i}\vert r_{j}\rangle & = & \delta_{ij}\nonumber \\
\langle s_{i}\vert s_{j}\rangle & = & \delta_{ij}\nonumber \\
\langle r_{i}\vert s_{j}\rangle & = & \delta_{ij}\cos\theta_{i}\label{eq:jordan}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to the Jordan structure, instead of one 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

 dimensional problem we have 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 mutually orthogonal 2-dimensional subspaces.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 subspace is spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert r_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert s_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 with 
\emph on
prior
\emph default
 probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}s_{i}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Thus the discrimination of the two mixed states 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}$
\end_inset

 can be reduced into that of pure state discrimination in each subspace,
 by discriminating 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert r_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert s_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 in each subspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we solve the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

, there is 2-dimensional subspaces for each density operator.
 The density operator in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "rho1and2"

\end_inset

) can be expressed as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\rho_{1} & = & r_{1}\ket{r_{1}}\bra{r_{1}}+r_{2}\ket{r_{2}}\bra{r_{2}},\nonumber \\
\rho_{2} & = & s_{1}\ket{s_{1}}\bra{s_{1}}+s_{2}\ket{s_{2}}\bra{s_{2}}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The overall error rate is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{E} & = & \eta_{1}tr\left(\Pi_{2}\rho_{1}\right)+\eta_{2}tr\left(\Pi_{1}\rho_{2}\right),\nonumber \\
 & = & \eta_{1}\left(r_{1}tr\left(\Pi_{s,1}\ket{r_{1}}\bra{r_{1}}\right)+r_{2}tr\left(\Pi_{s,2}\ket{r_{2}}\bra{r_{2}}\right)\right)+\label{eq:SubspaceErr}\\
 &  & \eta_{2}\left(s_{1}tr\left(\Pi_{r,1}\ket{s_{1}}\bra{s_{1}}\right)+s_{2}tr\left(\Pi_{r,2}\ket{s_{2}}\bra{s_{2}}\right)\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

In this case the first subspace is spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\vert r_{1}\rangle,\vert s_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 and the second subspace by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\vert r_{2}\rangle,\vert s_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

.
 The task becomes that of performing FRIO discrimination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\vert r_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert s_{i}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 within subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The error rate in each subspace is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{e,1} & = & \eta_{1}r_{1}tr\left(\Pi_{s,1}\ket{r_{1}}\bra{r_{1}}\right)+\eta_{2}s_{1}tr\left(\Pi_{r,1}\ket{s_{1}}\bra{s_{1}}\right)\nonumber \\
P_{e,1} & = & \eta_{1}r_{2}tr\left(\Pi_{s,2}\ket{r_{2}}\bra{r_{2}}\right)+\eta_{2}s_{2}tr\left(\Pi_{r,2}\ket{s_{2}}\bra{s_{2}}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The prior probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert r_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}r_{i}$
\end_inset

 while the prior probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert s_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}s_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We define their normalized probabilities as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\eta_{1,i} & \equiv & \frac{\eta_{1}r_{i}}{\eta_{1}r_{i}+\eta_{2}s_{i}},\nonumber \\
\eta_{2,i} & \equiv & \frac{\eta_{2}s_{i}}{\eta_{1}r_{i}+\eta_{2}s_{i}}\ ,\label{etaij}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1,i}+\eta_{2,i}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The error rate in each subspace becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\tilde{P}_{e,1} & = & \eta_{1,1}tr\left(\Pi_{s,1}\ket{r_{1}}\bra{r_{1}}\right)+\eta_{2,1}tr\left(\Pi_{r,1}\ket{s_{1}}\bra{s_{1}}\right)\nonumber \\
\tilde{P}_{e,2} & = & \eta_{1,2}tr\left(\Pi_{s,2}\ket{r_{2}}\bra{r_{2}}\right)+\eta_{2,2}tr\left(\Pi_{r,2}\ket{s_{2}}\bra{s_{2}}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{P}_{e,i}=\frac{P_{e,i}}{\left(\eta_{1}r_{i}+\eta_{2}s_{i}\right)}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that this reduces the problem to the FRIO discrimination of two
 pure states in subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, with prior probabilities given above.
 It follows immediately that the solution is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PeSol1"

\end_inset

 in the POVM regime of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}\leq Q_{c,i},Q_{th,i}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PeSol2"

\end_inset

 in the projective regime of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{th,i}<Q_{i}\leq Q_{c,i}$
\end_inset

, again with the above substitutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following we will focus mainly on the POVM regime where the solution
 in each subspace is given explicitly by Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PeSol1"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{e,1} & = & \frac{1}{2}(1-Q_{1}-\sqrt{(1-Q_{1})^{2}-(Q_{0,1}-Q_{1})^{2}})\ ,\label{Pei2}\\
P_{e,2} & = & \frac{1}{2}(1-Q_{2}-\sqrt{(1-Q_{2})^{2}-(Q_{0,2}-Q_{2})^{2}})
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where we introduced a fixed rate of inconclusive outcomes for each subspace
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq Q_{i}\leq Q_{c,i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{c,i}$
\end_inset

 is given by Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qmax"

\end_inset

 with the obvious substitutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\rightarrow\eta_{1,i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}\rightarrow\eta_{2,i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\rightarrow\cos\theta_{i}=\langle r_{i}\vert s_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0,i}=2\sqrt{\eta_{1,i}\eta_{2,i}}\langle r_{i}|s_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 was introduced in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qmax"

\end_inset

 for the single subspace (two pure states) case, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0,i}$
\end_inset

 is its generalization for the case of two (or many) subspaces.
 We introduce the weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 of subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{1}r_{i}+\eta_{2}s_{i}=\omega_{i}\ ,\label{omegai}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where, obviously, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega_{1}+\omega_{2}=1\ .\label{weights}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total error rate in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SubspaceErr"

\end_inset

) can be expressed as weighted sum of the error rates of the individual
 subspaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{e} & = & \omega_{1}P_{e,1}+\omega_{2}P_{e,2}\ ,=\frac{\omega_{1}}{2}\left[\left(1-Q_{1}\right)-\sqrt{\left(1-Q_{1}\right)^{2}-\left(Q_{0,1}-Q_{1}\right)^{2}}\right]+\nonumber \\
 &  & \frac{\omega_{2}}{2}\left[\left(1-Q_{2}\right)-\sqrt{\left(1-Q_{2}\right)^{2}-\left(Q_{0,2}-Q_{2}\right)^{2}}\right]\label{eq:PeTotal}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The task it to determine the optimal distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 among the two subspaces, the distribution that minimizes the error rate
 for a fixed amount of inconclusive results.
 We can write the total inconclusive rate as a weighted of the inconclusive
 rates of the individual subspaces,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=\omega_{1}Q_{1}+\omega_{2}Q_{2}\ .\label{Qtot2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the total failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is fixed, then only one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}s$
\end_inset

 is an independent variable.
 Thus the total error rate can be expressed in terms of only one variable
 and be optimized in that variable.
 Inserting 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{2}=\left(Q-\omega_{1}Q_{1}\right)/\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 into Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PeTotal"

\end_inset

) it becomes a function of the independent variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the optimization with respect to this variable is straightforward:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{e} & = & \frac{\omega_{1}}{2}\left[\left(1-Q_{1}\right)-\sqrt{\left(1-Q_{1}\right)^{2}-\left(Q_{0,1}-Q_{1}\right)^{2}}\right]+\\
 &  & \frac{\omega_{2}}{2}\left[\left(1-\frac{Q}{\omega_{2}}+\frac{\omega_{1}Q_{1}}{\omega_{2}}\right)-\sqrt{\left(1-\frac{Q}{\omega_{2}}+\frac{\omega_{1}Q_{1}}{\omega_{2}}\right)^{2}-\left(Q_{0,2}-\frac{Q}{\omega_{2}}+\frac{\omega_{1}Q_{1}}{\omega_{2}}\right)^{2}}\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Simply setting the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial P_{e}}{\partial Q_{1}}=0$
\end_inset

 and solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1},$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
0=\frac{\partial P_{e}}{\partial Q_{1}} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[-\omega_{1}-\frac{\omega_{1}(1-Q_{0,1})}{\sqrt{\left(1-Q_{1}\right)^{2}-\left(Q_{0,1}-Q_{1}\right)^{2}}}\right]+\\
 &  & \frac{1}{2}\left[\omega_{1}-\frac{\omega_{1}(1-Q_{0,2})}{\sqrt{\left(1-\frac{Q}{\omega_{2}}+\frac{\omega_{1}Q_{1}}{\omega_{2}}\right)^{2}-\left(Q_{0,2}-\frac{Q}{\omega_{2}}+\frac{\omega_{1}Q_{1}}{\omega_{2}}\right)^{2}}}\right]\\
\\
\left(1-Q_{0,2}\right)^{2}\left[\left(1-Q_{1}\right)^{2}-\left(Q_{0,1}-Q_{1}\right)^{2}\right] & = & \left(1-Q_{0,2}\right)^{2}\left[\left(1-\frac{Q}{\omega_{2}}+\frac{\omega_{1}Q_{1}}{\omega_{2}}\right)^{2}-\left(Q_{0,2}-\frac{Q}{\omega_{2}}+\frac{\omega_{1}Q_{1}}{\omega_{2}}\right)^{2}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to express the optimal failure rates in compact form it will be
 useful to introduce at this point the following convention.
 Without loss of generality in what follows we assume the hierarchy 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{0,1}\geq Q_{0,2}\ .\label{hierarchy2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We also introduce the notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{th}^{(1)}\equiv0\ \ \ \ Q_{th}^{(2)}\equiv\frac{\omega_{1}(Q_{0,1}-Q_{0,2})}{1-Q_{0,2}}\ .\label{Qth12}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then result of the optimization can be written as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{1}^{opt}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
\frac{Q}{\omega_{1}} & \mbox{if \ensuremath{Q_{th}^{(1)}\leq Q\leq Q_{th}^{(2)}}},\\
\frac{1-Q_{0,1}}{1-Q_{0}}(Q-Q_{th}^{(2)})+\frac{Q_{th}^{(2)}}{\omega_{1}} & \mbox{if \ensuremath{Q_{th}^{(2)}<Q\leq Q_{0}}},
\end{array}\right.\label{eq:Q1opt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Q_{2}^{opt}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
0 & \mbox{if \ensuremath{0\leq Q\leq Q_{th}^{(2)}}},\\
\frac{1-Q_{0,2}}{1-Q_{0}}(Q-Q_{th}^{(2)}) & \mbox{if \ensuremath{Q_{th}^{(2)}<Q\leq Q_{0}}}.
\end{array}\right.\label{Q2opt}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The threshold structure is the interesting feature of this problem.
 In the region 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq Q\leq Q_{th}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

 only one of the subspaces accommodates the fixed failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, it is the subspace with the larger 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0,i}$
\end_inset

.
 The other subspace allows for no inconclusive rate at all, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

, and operates in the Minimum Error regime.
 Above this threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{Q_{th}^{(2)}<Q\leq Q_{0}}$
\end_inset

, both subspaces share the failure rate but at different values.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}Q_{0,1}>\omega_{2}Q_{0,2}$
\end_inset

, the first subspace always accommodates more inconclusive rate than the
 second, otherwise above some value of the total 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 the second subspace will accommodate more inconclusive rate than the first.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The situation is depicted in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Fig2"

\end_inset

, for some specific values of the parameters.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement ht
wide false
sideways false
status open

