\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 (solid line) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}P_{e,{\rm 2}}^{{\rm opt}}$
\end_inset

 vs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 (dashed line).
 For the figure we used the same parameter values as in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Fig2"

\end_inset

.
 The insert in (b) shows that the solid and dashed lines intersect for a
 very small value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Fig3"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
FRIO discrimination of two Rank 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 mixed states, POVM regime
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we present the more general solution to the two rank 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 density matrices, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is some arbitrary but fixed integer.
 The two density matrices exhibit the Jordan basis as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "rho1and2"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:jordan"

\end_inset

.
 Solving the problem is very similar to the method for two rank 2 mixed
 states in the preceding section.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definitions and properties presented in Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:jordan"

\end_inset

--
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "omegai"

\end_inset

 remain in effect but the part starting with Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "weights"

\end_inset

 has to be modified accordingly.The weights of the subspaces, introduced
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "omegai"

\end_inset

 now satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i=1}^{N}\omega_{i}=1\ .\label{Nweights}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total inconclusive rate can again be written as a weighted sum of the
 inconclusive rates of the individual subspaces, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\omega_{i}Q_{i}\ .\label{NQtot}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is fixed, with the fixed value satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq Q\leq Q_{0}$
\end_inset

, where now 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{0}\equiv\sum_{i=1}^{N}\omega_{i}Q_{0,i}\ ,\label{NQ0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 is the maximal inconclusive rate that the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 subspaces can accommodate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, the total error rate is a weighted sum of the error rates of
 the individual subspaces, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{e}=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\omega_{i}P_{e,i}\ .\label{NPe}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remaining task is to determine the optimal distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 between the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 subspaces, the distribution that minimizes the total error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

, under the constraint that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "NQtot"

\end_inset

 is fixed, i.e., to determine the optimal values of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to perform the optimization we employ the Lagrange multiplier method
 because it leads to symmetric and easily tractable equations.
 Adding the Lagrange multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 times the constraint, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q-\sum_{i=1}^{N}Q_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "NPe"

\end_inset

 yields the function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\omega_{i}P_{e,i}+\lambda(Q-\sum_{i=1}^{N}\omega_{i}Q_{i})\ ,\label{constrainedF}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e,i}$
\end_inset

 is inserted from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Pei2"

\end_inset

, so it is also a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Next we vary 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 treating the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1},Q_{2},....,Q_{N}$
\end_inset

 as independent.
 Solving the resulting equations together with the constraint (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "NQtot"

\end_inset

) determines the value of the Lagrange multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 which in return optimizes 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "NPe"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we present the results it will prove useful to introduce a hierarchy
 of the subspaces.
 So, in what follows we will assume 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{0,1}\geq Q_{0,2}\geq\ldots\geq Q_{0,N}\ ,\label{hierarchy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which generalizes the ordering used in the case of two subspaces in the
 previous section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Q_{i}^{opt}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
\frac{1-Q_{0,i}}{\sum_{i=1}^{k}\omega_{i}-\sum_{i=1}^{k}\omega_{i}Q_{0,i}}Q+\frac{Q_{0,i}\sum_{i=1}^{k}\omega_{i}-\sum_{i=1}^{k}\omega_{i}Q_{0,i}}{\sum_{i=1}^{k}\omega_{i}-\sum_{i=1}^{k}\omega_{i}Q_{0,i}} & \ \ \ \\
\mbox{if \ensuremath{Q_{th}^{(k)}\leq Q\leq Q_{th}^{(k+1)}} and \ensuremath{i\leq k}}\ ,\\
0\\
\mbox{if \ensuremath{i>k}}\ .
\end{array}\right.\label{Qiopt}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,\ldots,N$
\end_inset

 and we introduced the notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{th}^{(k)}=\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{k}\omega_{i}Q_{0,i}-Q_{0,k}\sum_{i=1}^{k}\omega_{i}}{1-Q_{0,k}}\ .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and also 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{th}^{(N+1)}=Q_{0}=Q_{max}$
\end_inset

, cf.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "NQ0"

\end_inset

.
 Obviously, for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2$
\end_inset

 these results reproduce the results for two subspaces, Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qth12"

\end_inset

--
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Q2opt"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inserting the optimal failure rates into the subspace-error rates 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e,i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Pei2"

\end_inset

, gives the optimal error rates for the subspaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e,i}^{opt}$
\end_inset

.
 Then using these optimal subspace-error rates in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "NPe"

\end_inset

 gives the total optimal error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\sum_{i=1}^{N}P_{e,i}^{opt}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{E}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
\frac{1}{2}\left[1-Q-\sqrt{\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k}\omega_{i}-Q\right)^{2}-\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k}\omega_{i}Q_{0,i}-Q\right)^{2}}-\sum_{i=k+1}^{N}\sqrt{(\omega_{i})^{2}-\left(\omega_{i}Q_{0,i}\right)^{2}}\right] & \mbox{ if \ensuremath{Q_{th}^{(k)}\leq Q\leq Q_{th}^{(k+1)}}}\\
{} & \mbox{ and \ensuremath{k<N}}\ ,\\
\frac{1}{2}\!\left[1-Q-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-\left(Q_{0}-Q\right)^{2}}\right] & \mbox{ if \ensuremath{Q_{th}^{(N)}<Q\leq Q_{0}}}\ ,
\end{array}\right.\label{eq:PEN}\\
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

which is valid in all regions of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PEN"

\end_inset

 reduces to the two-subspaces solution, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PE2"

\end_inset

.
 For the maximum allowable inconclusive rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{0}$
\end_inset

, the second line in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PEN"

\end_inset

 holds and it reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=0$
\end_inset

, corresponding to optimal Unambiguous Discrimination of the subspaces ,
 while for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

 the first line holds and it reduces to the Minimum Error expression for
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 subspaces , as expected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, the most interesting aspect of the optimal solution is that a structure
 with multiple thresholds emerges.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{th}^{(1)}=0\leq Q<Q_{th}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

 the total available inconclusive rate is accommodated by the first subspace
 only and all others operate at the Minimum Error level.
 According to the hierarchy introduced in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "hierarchy"

\end_inset

, the first subspace is the one with the largest 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0,i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then between 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{th}^{(2)}\leq Q<Q_{th}^{(3)}$
\end_inset

 the second subspace, the one with the second largest 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0,i}$
\end_inset

 will also participate in sharing the available inconclusive rate, while
 the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $N-2$
\end_inset

 subspaces continue to operate at the minimum error level.
 In general, in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{th}^{(k)}\leq Q<Q_{th}^{(k+1)}$
\end_inset

 the first 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 subspaces share the available inconclusive rate and the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $N-k$
\end_inset

 subspaces remain at the minimum error level.
 Finally, in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{th}^{(N)}\leq Q\leq Q_{0}=Q_{max}$
\end_inset

 all 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 subspaces participate in sharing the available inconclusive rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to show that the expressions are continuous at the threshold,
 i.e.
 the expressions valid below the threshold and the ones valid above the
 threshold tend to the same values at the threshold, although their slopes
 are, in general, different below and above the threshold.
 Furthermore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}Q_{0,i}>\omega_{i+1}Q_{0,i+1}$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 subspace always accommodates more inconclusive rate than the 
\begin_inset Formula $i+1^{st}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,\ldots,N$
\end_inset

, otherwise above some value of the total 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $i+1^{st}$
\end_inset

 subspace will accommodate more inconclusive rate than the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 subspace, the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}^{opt}(Q)$
\end_inset

 curves will intersect (see part (b) of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Fig2"

\end_inset

 for an example).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We illustrate these results on the example of 
\begin_inset Formula $N=3$
\end_inset

.
 In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Fig4"

\end_inset

, we plot the optimal failure rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}Q_{i}^{{\rm opt}}$
\end_inset

 and in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Fig5"

\end_inset

, we plot the optimal error rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}P_{e,i}^{{\rm opt}}$
\end_inset

 for the three subspaces as a function of the total failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 for some specific values of the parameters.
 
