\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal error rates also exhibit a threshold structure.
 Relative to the POVM regime, the SQM shifts the threshold to a higher value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 and the overall error rate also increases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Summary and conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have found analytic solutions for the optimal discrimination measurement
 strategy when a fixed rate of inconclusive outcomes, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, is allowed (FRIO strategy), for a class of mixed states that exhibit a
 Jordan Basis structure.
 Thus our work extends the previously introduced FRIO strategy from pure
 states 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan2012"

\end_inset

 to mixed states.
 In this strategy the probability of making an error in identifying the
 state, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

, is minimized for a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 and the solution optimally interpolates between the minimum error (
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

) and unambiguous discrimination (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}=0$
\end_inset

) limits.
 We found several surprising and unexpected conclusions.
 The first is that the form of the optimal error rate remains formally the
 same over all subspaces as in the case of two pure states, which is a consequen
ce of the Jordan structure of the mixed states.
 The second is a more striking feature, the emergence of a threshold structure:
 as we increase the allowed inconclusive rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, starting from 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

, at first only one subspace accommodates all of the available 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Above a certain threshold a second subspace starts sharing the available
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, above yet another higher threshold a third subspace starts participating,
 etc., until above a final threshold all of the subspaces participate.
 It is interesting to note that in this last regime the optimal error expression
 the second line in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PEN"

\end_inset

 is formally the same as the result for two pure states.
 This is a novel type of behavior and allows for experimental tests of our
 findings.
 Applications could be considered in cryptography where a key is shared
 over different lines to enhance security without sacrificing overall error
 rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Quantum Cloning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the reasons we need to develop optimum state discrimination measurement
 schemes is due to the no cloning theorem of Wootters, Zurek 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wootters1982"

\end_inset

 and Dieks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dieks1982"

\end_inset

.
 If one could copy non-orthogonal quantum states then by making a very large
 number of copies, it would be possible to distinguish the states.
 However cloning machines which optimize some criteria with a limited degree
 of success have been developed.
 Those cloning machines fall under two categories: universal and state dependent.
 Universal cloning machines, which make copies of a completely unknown quantum
 state, were developed first by Buzek and Hillery 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Buzek1996"

\end_inset

.
 This scheme makes approximate copies of an unknown quantum state while
 optimizing the local fidelity which is the square overlap of the approximate
 clones and the original state it is supposed to clone.
 The other category is state dependent cloning machines.
 In this scheme the observer has full knowledge of the prepared states but
 does not know which is the state he is given.
 There are two subcategories within this scheme: approximate and exact cloning.
 Approximate state-dependent cloning machines deterministically generate
 approximate clones from a finite set of non-orthogonal quantum states while
 optimizing the local or global fidelity (the average square overlap between
 full set of approximate clones and the states to be cloned).
 Hillery and Buzek 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hillery1997"

\end_inset

 are the pioneers of this subcategory of cloning machines as well.
 In exact state-dependent cloning machines, the other subcategory of quantum
 cloning machines, the task is to probabilistically make exact copies of
 the incoming non-orthogonal quantum states.
 This comes at the expense of allowing for failure results where the scheme
 fails to produce a copy altogether.
 Duan and Guo 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duan1998"

\end_inset

 were first to develop probabilistic exact cloning machines for the two
 state input where the states are prepared with equal a priori probabilities.
 We recently extended this method for the more general case where the a
 priori probabilities of the incoming states are different [].
 This extension not only solves the full problem but gives new insight into
 the nature of quantum cloning.
 The symmetry of the equal priors case completely solves the problem and
 no further optimization can be done.
 This symmetry however hides the true nature of the exact cloning machines
 which show up in the unequal priors case.
 This can be shown through a two step process: exact cloning then optimal
 UD on the clones.
 First procedure makes exact clones of the incoming two states.
 The exact clones are then sent to an optimal UD machine where the average
 failure rate is minimized.
 To combine the two step process the inconclusive rate from the cloning
 process is added to the inconclusive rate, weighed with the new a-priori
 probabilities, from the optimal UD.
 When the input states are prepared with equal a-priors the total amount
 of the inconclusive rate reaches the IDP limit.
 Hence cloning then performing optimal UD is equivalent to simply performing
 the optimal UD first, then prepare the clones.
 However this is not true for when the priors of the input states are different.
 After the two step process the total inconclusive rate is higher then the
 IDP limit.
 This suggests that during the cloning process some information is being
 leaked due to the asymmetry of the failure rate operators.
 When performing exact cloning, clones are produced but no measurement has
 been made, hence we do not know which states are being cloned.
 We simply know whether the procedure was successful or it failed.
 When it fails, the states are discarded.
 This is where the information leakage comes in.
 The state which is prepared most often shall have a higher rate of failure.
 This does not happen in the equal priors case because the failure rate
 are symmetric.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
No-Cloning Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some of the schemes described in this dissertation related to discriminate
 quantum states would not be necessary if one could make copies of the non-ortho
gonal quantum states as can be done with classical states.
 If this were possible then the receiver, Bob, after receiving the state
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 from the preparer, Alice, makes 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 number of copies.
 After a large set of copies the states become nearly orthogonal and almost
 fully distinguishable.
 The average inconclusive rate of failing to distinguish the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 copies of 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}=2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s^{n}.$
\end_inset

 For a large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 the inconclusive rate is very small and Bob can discriminate nearly all
 incoming states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus while in classical information it is possible to make exact copies
 of information, as this dissertation is printed on this paper, multiple
 times by a printer.
 The no-cloning theorem forbids the receiver doing the same with quantum
 states.
 More specifically it is non-orthogonal quantum states which cannot be copied,
 as classical states are a special case of quantum states, that of orthogonal
 states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now show a proof by contradiction of why such a quantum cloning machine
 cannot exist.
 Suppose there is such a cloning machine with an input and an output port.
 Inside the machine there are two slots: slot 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 for the system state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 to be copied, and slot 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 for the ancilla state for where the input state is to be copied.
 Let the ancilla be in some blank space 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle,$
\end_inset

 then the initial state of the copying machine would be: 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle|0\rangle.$
\end_inset

 A unitary operator would copy the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U|\psi_{i}\rangle|0\rangle=|\psi_{i}\rangle|\psi_{i}\rangle
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let there be two possible input states to be copied, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 and we are interested in a quantum cloning machine which produces 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is sent and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is sent.
 The unitary operator would do the following.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle|0\rangle & = & |\psi_{1}\rangle|\psi_{1}\rangle\nonumber \\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle|0\rangle & = & |\psi_{2}\rangle|\psi_{2}\rangle
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product of these equations gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\psi_{2}|\psi_{1}\rangle\langle0|0\rangle=|\langle\psi_{2}|\psi_{1}\rangle|^{2}\Rightarrow s=s^{2}.$
\end_inset

 This condition can be satisfied only if 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0$
\end_inset

, states are orthogonal, or 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1,$
\end_inset

 the two states are the same.
 But we said that the two states are distinct and non-orthogonal.
 Thus one cannot design a unitary device which makes perfect clones of an
 unknown quantum system deterministically.
 Here we only proved that non-orthogonal pure states cannot be copied through
 a unitary process.
 Other proofs exist which show that this holds for mixed states and also
 for other non-unitary processes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since such a machine cannot be designed the next logical step is to build
 a quantum machine which produces clones similar to the input states while
 allowing for some fidelity or inconclusive results.
 We derive some previous results considering such quantum cloning machines
 and also provide new results for optimal exact cloning with some inconclusive
 rate allowed.
 In a follow up section we interpolate between the deterministic cloning
 scheme and exact cloning by relaxing some of the conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Exact cloning with failure rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In probabilistic cloning we are concerned with making exact copies of the
 given quantum state.
 It is indeed possible to make exact copies but only probabilistically.
 This is similar to the Unambiguous Discrimination where one discriminates
 between a given set of non-orthogonal quantum states unambiguously while
 allowing for a failure rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We approach probabilistic cloning via the Neumark formulation.
 The system is embedded in a larger Hilbert space where the extra degrees
 of freedom are customarily called the ancilla.
 Then a unitary transformation entangles the system degrees of freedom with
 those of the ancilla.
 The input states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}^{M}\rangle_{s},|\psi_{2}^{M}\rangle_{s}\}$
\end_inset

 which live in the state Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 are embedded with the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|i\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 which live in the 
\begin_inset Formula $N-M$
\end_inset

 dimensional Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $A.$
\end_inset

 Now the system and the ancilla live in the larger Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H=S\varotimes A.$
\end_inset

 The incoming states in this larger Hilbert space can be written in the
 product form 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}^{N}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a},|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a}\}.$
\end_inset

 The unitary should do the following: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}^{M}\rangle|i\rangle^{N-M} & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\psi_{1}^{N}\rangle|\alpha_{1}\rangle+\sqrt{q_{1}}|\Phi_{1}\rangle,\label{eq:clone1}\\
U|\psi_{2}^{M}\rangle|i\rangle^{N-M} & = & \sqrt{p_{2}}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|\alpha_{2}\rangle+\sqrt{q_{2}}|\Phi_{2}\rangle,\label{eq:clone2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the rate of having successfully produced a perfect clone, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the rate of having failed to do so.
 The inner product of each of the above equation with its own transpose
 gives the normalized probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}+q_{i}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 are the input states we wish to clone and their corresponding ancillas
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Getting a click in 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Phi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 means we have failed to clone and discard the state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the inner product of the transpose of equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:clone1"

\end_inset

) with (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:clone2"

\end_inset

) we get the constraint of success and failure rate in terms of the overlap
 of the input states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s^{M}=\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}s^{N}\alpha+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\phi
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle,\quad s'=\langle\Psi_{1}|\Psi_{2}\rangle,\quad\alpha=\langle\alpha_{1}|\alpha_{2}\rangle,\quad\phi=\langle\Phi_{1}|\Phi_{2}\rangle
\]

\end_inset

In the above setup the ancilla states corresponding to successfully making
 the clones are distinct.
 The failure states are also distinct.
 That is the most general case.
 In order for the success rates to be optimal we take the ancilla states
 to be the same.
 Looking at the constraint we absorb 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, meaning there is more copies which would come at the expense of a lower
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 .
 More explicitly this can be proved for the equal priors case shown below.
 We will now prove that the failure states should also be the same.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Phi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Phi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 are different that means that there is still information left in the failure
 states and we can still perform Unambiguous State discrimination and probabilis
tically determine whether we received 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 .
 The optimal strategy is one which leaves no information at all in the failure
 states, the overlap 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
of the failure states can be set to one 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\Phi_{2}|\Phi_{1}\rangle=1.$
\end_inset

 Any click from the failure state is simply discarded as failure.
 The revised Neumark setup reduces to: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}^{M}\rangle|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\psi_{1}^{N}\rangle\ket{\alpha}+\sqrt{q_{1}}|\Phi\rangle\ket 0,\nonumber \\
U|\psi_{2}^{M}\rangle|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{2}}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|\alpha\rangle+\sqrt{q_{2}}|\Phi\rangle\ket 0,
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The constraint simplifies into:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s^{M}=\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}s^{N}+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}.\label{eq:clone overlap}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the constraint on the parameters to optimize the average failure
 rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}.$
\end_inset

 The optimization is straightforward for the symmetric case where the input
 states are prepared with equal priors.
 The general case, states prepared with different a priori probabilities,
 leads to a sixth order equation the solution of which isn't very useful.
 A geometric picture however emerges which is more insightful.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equal priors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the input states are prepared with equal prior probabilities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=\frac{1}{2},$
\end_inset

 the problem is quite trivial.
 It was first solved by Duan and Guo 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duan1998"

\end_inset

.
 For equal priors the success and failure rate reduce to: 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=p_{2}=p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=q_{2}=q$
\end_inset

.
 The constraint in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:clone overlap"

\end_inset

) reduces to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s^{M}=ps^{N}+q,
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
using the unitarity condition 
\begin_inset Formula $p+q=1,$
\end_inset

 the problem can be fully solved:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
s^{M} & = & ps^{N}+(1-p),\nonumber \\
p & = & \frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the failure rate is 
\begin_inset Formula $q=1-p=\frac{s^{M}-s^{N}}{1-s^{N}}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the optimization of the probabilistic exact cloning is fully solved
 from the constraint derived from the Neumark method and no further optimization
 is needed.
 In the limit of producing infinitely many clones, 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, the failure rate reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula $q=s^{M},$
\end_inset

 which is also the IDP result for unambiguous state discrimination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Unequal priors I
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are a number of reasons why one might want to solve the general problem
 with arbitrary priori probabilities.
 (i)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The solution to the equal priors problem is obtained using only symmetry
 arguments, with no need for optimization.
 (ii)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A general solution would check the robustness of the equal priors case against
 variations of the prior probabilities around 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

.
 This gives control over errors that are unavoidable for any physical realizatio
n.
 (iii)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

One could consider a discrimination protocol consisting of optimal cloning
 followed by optimal Unambiguous Discrimination (UD) of the produced clones,
 which we will call discrimination by cloning.
 Surprisingly this is optimal for equal prior probabilities and for any
 number of clones (see below).
 This suggests that the equal priors case is very special and can provide
 a deceptive view of cloning.
 (iv)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In the limit of infinitely many clones, the optimal strategy prepares the
 clones according to the outcomes of UD of the input states.
 This is a particular case of a measure and prepare protocol, which we will
 call cloning by discrimination.
 Since the UD measurement varies over the range of prior probabilities (a
 3-outcome generalized measurement vs a 2-outcome projective measurement),
 this hints at the possibility of a similar situation for optimal cloning
 that can only be decided by solving the general problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our solution shows that discrimination by cloning as outlined in (iii) is
 sub-optimal for unequal prior probabilities (unless one state is never
 sent).
 This indicates that the equal prior case is not representative of state
 dependent cloning.
 Additionally, contrary to the suggestions in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(iv) above, our solution leads to a failure probability that is a smooth
 function of the priors.
 However, the strategy converges to cloning by discrimination as
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

, implying a discontinuous second derivative of the total inconclusive rate
 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and revealing a phenomenon similar to a second order phase transition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can imagine a state dependent probabilistic cloner as a machine with
 an input port, an output port and two flags that herald the success or
 failure of cloning.
 The input 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}^{M}\rangle=|\psi_{i}\rangle^{\otimes M}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 identical copies of either 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

) is fed through the input port for processing.
 In case of success 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 perfect clones
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}^{N}\rangle=|\psi_{i}\rangle^{\otimes N}$
\end_inset

 are delivered through the output port with conditioned probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Otherwise, the output is in a refuse state.
 Conditioned on the input state being 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}^{M}\rangle$
\end_inset

, the failure probability is
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}=1-p_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For cloning, optimality is usually addressed from a Bayesian viewpoint that
 assumes the states to be cloned are given with some prior probabilities
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then a natural cost function for our probabilistic machines is given by
 the average failure probability 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}.\label{obj fun}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Accordingly, the optimal cloner minimizes the cost function 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Accordingly, the optimal cloner is one that minimizes the cost function
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Our aim is to find the optimal cloner and the minimum average failure probabili
ty 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 for arbitrary priors 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%The cloning process can be thought of as a generalized measurement and
 can be described by two operators~
\backslash
mbox{$A_{
\backslash
rm succ}$, $A_{
\backslash
rm fail}$}, so that~$A^
\backslash
dagger{}_{
\backslash
kern-.3em
\backslash
rm succ}A_{
\backslash
rm succ}+A^
\backslash
dagger{}_{
\backslash
kern-.2em
\backslash
rm fail}A_{
\backslash
rm fail}=
\backslash
openone$.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%However, Neumark's theorem~
\backslash
cite{Bergou} provides an alternative approach  that turns out to be more
 convenient for our analysis.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our formulation, similar to that in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duan1998"

\end_inset

, the Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula ${\mathscr{H}}^{\otimes M}$
\end_inset

 of the original 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 copies is supplemented by an ancillary space
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula ${\mathscr{H}}^{\otimes(N-M)}\otimes{\mathscr{H}}_{F}$
\end_inset

 that accommodates both the additional 
\begin_inset Formula $N-M$
\end_inset

 clones as well as the success/failure flags.
 Then, a unitary transformation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 (time evolution) from 
\begin_inset Formula ${\mathscr{H}}^{\otimes M}\otimes{\mathscr{H}}^{\otimes(N-M)}\otimes{\mathscr{H}}_{F}$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula ${\mathscr{H}}^{\otimes N}\otimes{\mathscr{H}}_{F}$
\end_inset

 is defined through
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duan1998"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U|\psi_{i}^{M}\rangle|0\rangle=\sqrt{p_{i}}|\psi_{i}^{N}\rangle|\alpha_{i}\rangle+\sqrt{q}_{i}|\Phi\rangle,\quad i=1,2.\label{Ui}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here the ancillas are initialized in a reference state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ket 0$
\end_inset

.
 The states of the flag associated with successful cloning
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\alpha_{i}}$
\end_inset

 are constrained to be orthogonal to the refuse state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Phi}$
\end_inset

 for certainty in the outcomes of the projective measurement on the flag
 space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathscr{H}_{F}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Although for optimal cloning 
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha_{1}\rangle=|\alpha_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, we need to consider a more general setup where these two states are different
 to include the cloning-by-discrimination protocol where UD is used to identify
 the input state and then the clones are prepared accordingly
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Likewise, we could consider a more general setup with two refuse states
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Phi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Phi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 in Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Ui"

\end_inset

).
 This is necessarily sub-optimal since we could probabilistically determine
 whether we received 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 by applying UD to the refuse states 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Phi_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 Sometimes we would be certain of the input state, when we can always prepare
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 copies of the state, thereby increasing the overall success rate of the
 cloning strategy.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 For UD the success flag states must be distinguishable, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\alpha_{1}|\alpha_{2}\rangle=0$
\end_inset

.
 Taking the inner product of each equation with itself shows that our probabilit
ies are normalized: 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}+q_{i}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, by taking the product of the two equations in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Ui"

\end_inset

), we find the unitarity constraint 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s^{M}=\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}\,s^{N}\alpha+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}},\label{unit cond}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the overlaps 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\braket{\psi_{1}}{\psi_{2}},\ 0\le s\le1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\langle\alpha_{1}|\alpha_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 can be chosen to be real valued without any loss of generality.
 .
 We note that for optimal cloning one has
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

, whereas
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 for cloning by discrimination.
 If Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) is satisfied, it is not hard to prove that
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 has a unitary extension on the whole space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../2ndDraft/Fig_1NC.pdf
	width 8.5cm
	height 8.5cm

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space \hspace{}
\length 1cm
\end_inset

Unitarity curves 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Unitarity curves in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) and the associated sets
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $S_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "S_alpha"

\end_inset

) for values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 positive (solid/light
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

gray), zero (dashed/medium gray), and negative (dotted/dark gray).
 The figure also shows the optimal straight segment 
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "c"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "c"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 1
width ""
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and its normal vector
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{1},\eta_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Plotted for 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0.5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.8,0,-0.8$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:1"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before attempting to minimize 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, we need to gain geometric insight into the meaning of the unitary constraint.
 The following points turn out to be important: (a)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) defines a class of smooth curves on the unit square 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le q_{i}\le1$
\end_inset

 (e.g., solid, dashed or dotted curves in Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1"

\end_inset

).
 (b)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

All these curves meet at their endpoints, 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,s^{2M})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(s^{2M},1)$
\end_inset

.
 (c)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

At the endpoints the curves become tangent to the vertical and horizontal
 lines
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}=1$
\end_inset

 respectively, provided
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\not=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%This is due to the square root $
\backslash
sqrt{p_1p_2}$ in Eq.~(
\backslash
ref{unit cond}).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%A more detailed analysis shows that f
\end_layout

\end_inset

(d)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 the curve 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%defined by Eq.~(
\backslash
ref{unit cond}) 
\end_layout

\end_inset

is an arc of the hyperbola 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}q_{2}=s^{2M}$
\end_inset

 (dashed line in Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1"

\end_inset

).
 (e)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Each of these curves and the segments joining their end points with the
 vertex
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(1,1)$
\end_inset

 are the boundary of the sets (any of the gray regions in Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{\alpha}=\{(q_{1},q_{2}):\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}\,s^{N}\alpha+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}-s^{M}\ge0\}.\label{S_alpha}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

They satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\alpha}\subset S_{\alpha'}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha<\alpha'$
\end_inset

.
 (f)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Moreover, the sets
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $S_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are convex if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\ge0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%For $
\backslash
alpha
\backslash
ge0$ the set $S_
\backslash
alpha$ is convex, as follows from the observation that~$(xy)^{1/2}$ is a
 concave function of its two (non-negative) arguments~$x$ and~$y$.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At this point a geometrical picture of the optimization problem emerges
 (See Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1"

\end_inset

).
 Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

) defines a straight segment on the square 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le q_{i}\le1$
\end_inset

 with a normal vector in the first quadrant parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{1},\eta_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 For fixed prior probabilities, the average failure probability
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the distance from this segment to the origin
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 is convex and the stretch of its boundary given by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

 is smooth, a unique point 
\begin_inset Formula $(q_{1},q_{2})$
\end_inset

 of tangency with the segment
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

) exists for any value of the priors and finite 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 It gives 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 and defines the optimal cloning strategy.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%(See Fig.~
\backslash
ref{fig:1}).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note in passing that the inclusion hierarchy of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 provides a simple geometrical proof that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha_{1}\rangle=|\alpha_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, is indeed the optimal choice.
 On the other hand, we recall that for cloning by discrimination we have
 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\alpha_{1}|\alpha_{2}\rangle=\alpha=0$
\end_inset

.
 From points
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(b) and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(c) above, it follows that for any finite 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and arbitrary priors 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 this protocol is strictly suboptimal, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}<Q_{{\rm UD}}$
\end_inset

, where the subscript UD is a reminder that the failure rate of cloning
 by discrimination is that of UD.
 One could say that optimal cloning is incompatible with discerning the
 identity of the input states for any finite number of clones.
 However, optimal cloning and UD become one and the same in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{N}\to0$
\end_inset

 and the curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) collapses to the hyperbola 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}q_{2}=s^{2M}$
\end_inset

, as it does for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

.
 We will come back to this point below.
 A more quantitative analysis requires finding a convenient parametrization
 of the curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

).
 To this end, simpler and more manageable expressions are derived if the
 symmetry under 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}\leftrightarrow q_{2}$
\end_inset

 is preserved.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{q_{i}}=\sin\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\theta_{i}\leq\pi/2$
\end_inset

.
 By further introducing the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\cos(\theta_{1}+\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\cos(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

 we manage to linearize the constraint
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

), which now reads as 
\begin_inset Formula $2s^{M}=(1+s^{N})y-(1-s^{N})x$
\end_inset

.
 A natural parametrization for this straight line is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=\frac{1-(1+s^{N})t}{s^{N-M}},\qquad y=\frac{1-(1-s^{N})t}{s^{N-M}},\label{x & y}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where again we have taken the most symmetrical choice.
 Because of the symmetry of this procedure, the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are invariant under 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}\leftrightarrow q_{2}$
\end_inset

 (equivalently, under 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}\leftrightarrow\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

).
 Thus, the two mirror halves of the curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) under this transformation are mapped into the same straight line
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "x & y"

\end_inset

).
 By expressing 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 as a function of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 only half of the original curve is recovered.
 The other half is trivially obtained by applying
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}\leftrightarrow q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The allowed domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "x & y"

\end_inset

) follows from that of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, readily seen from their definition to be the region 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|\le y\le1$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1-s^{n-m}}{1-s^{n}}\le t\le1.\label{range t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

After putting the various pieces together one can easily get rid of the
 trigonometric functions and express Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) in parametric form as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{i}=\frac{1-xy-(-1)^{i}\sqrt{1-x^{2}}\sqrt{1-y^{2}}}{2},\quad i=1,2.\label{par sqrt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:2"

\end_inset

 shows examples of the unitary curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) for (a)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 and (b)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n=5$
\end_inset

.
 In both cases 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

.
 For larger 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 the curves closely approximate the hyperbolae 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}q_{2}=s^{2m}$
\end_inset

 (dashed lines) for small and moderate values of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, while for 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 close to one the hyperbolas remain closer to the vertex
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(1,1)$
\end_inset

, but still retain the same end points.
 As mentioned previously, in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

 all curves become hyperbolic.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement hh
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../2ndDraft/Fig_2NC.pdf
	width 8.5cm
	height 8.5cm

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space \hspace{}
\length 1cm
\end_inset

Unitarity curves for s 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Unitarity curves for different values of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and for (a) 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 and (b) 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=5$
\end_inset

.
 The curves are symmetric under mirror reflexion along the (dotted) straight
 line 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=q_{2}$
\end_inset

, i.e., under the transformation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}\leftrightarrow q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The dashed lines in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(b) are the hyperbolae
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}q_{2}=s^{2m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:2"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can return to the minimization of the average failure probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Despite the apparent simplicity of the problem, finding the minimum 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 as an explicit function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 involves solving a quartic equation without a simple form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

 Instead, we will derive the parametric equation of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{1},Q_{{\rm min}})$
\end_inset

.
 This, along with our complete description of the unitary curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

, provides a full account of the solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Without any loss of generality we may assume that
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\le\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, or equivalently, that
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $0\le\eta_{1}\le1/2$
\end_inset

.
 Then the slope of the vector normal to the straight line
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

) is less or equal to one and thus it can only become tangent to the lower
 half of the unitary curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) (see Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:2"

\end_inset

).
 The slope of this lower half increases monotonically as we move away from
 the line
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=q_{2}$
\end_inset

, where it has the value
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, and vanishes before we reach the line
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=1$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from the properties (a)--(f) above and can be checked using
 Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "par sqrt"

\end_inset

).
 The values of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 at which the slope is 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 are respectively 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t_{-1}=\frac{1-s^{n-m}}{1-s^{n}},\quad t_{0}=\frac{1-s^{2(n-m)}}{1-s^{2n}},\label{t's}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we note that 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the lower value of the range of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "range t"

\end_inset

).
 For any point 
\begin_inset Formula $(q_{1}(t),q_{2}(t))$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[t_{-1},t_{0}]$
\end_inset

 there is a line 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}$
\end_inset

 that is tangent to it, starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=1/2$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{-1}$
\end_inset

 up to 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}=1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This observation enables us to derive the desired parametric expression
 for the optimality curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{1},Q_{{\rm min}})$
\end_inset

 as follows: for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in the range above, a necessary condition for tangency is 
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "c"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "c"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 1
width ""
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q'_{1}+\eta_{2}q'_{2}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $q'_{i}=dq_{i}/dt$
\end_inset

.
 In this equation we can solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

) using that
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 By substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

) with
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "par sqrt"

\end_inset

) we enforce contact with the unitarity curve and obtain the expression
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

.
 The final result can be cast as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{1}=\frac{q'_{2}}{q'_{2}-q'_{1}},\;\;Q_{{\rm min}}=\frac{q'_{2}q_{1}-q'_{1}q_{2}}{q'_{2}-q'_{1}},\;\;t_{-1}\le t\le t_{0},\label{main}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{-1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 are given in Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "t's"

\end_inset

) and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "par sqrt"

\end_inset

).
 The expressions for the derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $q'_{i}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%most easily derived from the trigonometric form~(
\backslash
ref{par trig}) to be
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q'_{i}=\frac{\sqrt{q_{i}(1-q_{i})}}{s^{n-m}}\left\{ \frac{1+s^{n}}{\sqrt{1-x^{2}}}-(-1)^{i}\frac{1-s^{n}}{\sqrt{1-y^{2}}}\right\} .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:3"

\end_inset

 shows plots of the curves 
\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{1},Q_{{\rm min}})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 input copies and (a) 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 or (b) 
\begin_inset Formula $n=5$
\end_inset

 clones, as in the previous figure.
 We see that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 is an increasing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 in the given range 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1/2]$
\end_inset

.
 The values of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 at the end points of this range follow by substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{-1}$
\end_inset

, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "t's"

\end_inset

), into Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "par sqrt"

\end_inset

).
 They are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{0}=q_{2}(t_{0})=\frac{s^{2m}-s^{2n}}{1-s^{2n}},\quad Q_{-1}=\frac{s^{m}-s^{n}}{1-s^{n}},\label{Q's}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}=Q_{-1}$
\end_inset

 holds for equal priors and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}=Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\to0$
\end_inset

 (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}\to1$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../2ndDraft/Fig_3NC.pdf
	width 8cm
	height 6cm

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space \hspace{}
\length 1cm
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Minimum cloning failure probability 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 (solid lines) and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

UD failure probability 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm UD}}$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 (dashed lines) for the same values of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 used in the previous figure.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:3"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset

The dashed lines in Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:3"

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(b) are the well known piecewise unambiguous discrimination solution
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bergou2010"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{{\rm UD}}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
\eta_{1}+s^{2m}\eta_{2},\quad & {\displaystyle 0\le\eta_{1}\le\frac{s^{2m}}{1+s^{2m}};}\\[0.5em]
2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}\,s^{m}, & {\displaystyle \frac{s^{2m}}{1+s^{2m}}\le\eta_{1}\le\frac{1}{2}.}
\end{array}\right.\label{UD-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is apparent from these plots that the optimal cloning protocol performs
 strictly better than cloning by discrimination, as was proved above.
 However, as the number of produced clones becomes larger the difference
 in performance reduces.
 In Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:3"

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(b), for only 
\begin_inset Formula $n=5$
\end_inset

, a difference is hardly noticeable for 
\begin_inset Formula $s\le0.5$
\end_inset

.
 For larger overlaps it takes larger values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 to get the same level of agreement.
 As discussed above, in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

 there is perfect agreement for any 
\begin_inset Formula $s<1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The complete UD solution in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD-1"

\end_inset

) emerges naturally from our geometrical approach in a straightforward manner:
 First, we recall that in this case the right hand side of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}q_{2}=s^{2m}$
\end_inset

 (dashed lines in Figs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:2"

\end_inset

).
 The maximum slopes of these curves are at their end points and all have
 the value
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $-s^{2m}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that the boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 has a cusp at 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,s^{2m})$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that a unique point of tangency with the line
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

) exists for 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2m}<\eta_{1}/\eta_{2}\le1$
\end_inset

 (recall that we are assuming
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\le1/2$
\end_inset

).
 This condition gives the 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 interval for that solution.
 The tangency condition, 
\begin_inset Formula $(q_{2},q_{1})\propto(\eta_{1},\eta_{2})$
\end_inset

, quickly leads us to the optimal failure rate in the second line of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD-1"

\end_inset

).
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2m}>\eta_{1}/\eta_{2}\ge0$
\end_inset

 tangency is not possible, and the optimal line
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

) merely touches the cusp on the boundary of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

, so the expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 becomes the first line of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD-1"

\end_inset

).
 In geometrical terms, the straight line
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

) pivots on the end point as 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 varies between 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2m}/(1+s^{2m})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the second case in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD-1"

\end_inset

), one has 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1},p_{1}\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and there are three orthogonal flag states in Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Ui"

\end_inset

), namely, the two success states 
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, and the failure state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $|\Phi\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 This 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-outcome measurement can be represented by a 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-element positive operator valued measure (POVM) on 
\begin_inset Formula ${\mathscr{H}}^{\otimes m}$
\end_inset

.
 For the first line in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD-1"

\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=1-q_{1}=0$
\end_inset

, which leads to a 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-outcome projective measurement, as only one success flag state (
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

) is needed in Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Ui"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This two-paragraph derivation of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD-1"

\end_inset

) proves that the convergence of the optimal cloning failure probability
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 to that of cloning by discrimination, with rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm UD}}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD-1"

\end_inset

), follows from the convergence of the general unitarity curve in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) to the hyperbola 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}q_{2}=s^{2m}$
\end_inset

, i.e., from 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{\alpha\to0}S_{\alpha}=S_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Interestingly enough, such convergence entails a phenomenon analogous to
 a second order phase transition.
 Our geometrical approach shows that the average failure probability 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}(\eta_{1})$
\end_inset

 is an infinitely differentiable function of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 for finite 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 However, as 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 goes to infinity (or at 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

, for the sake of this discussion) the limiting function 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm UD}}(\eta_{1})$
\end_inset

 has a discontinuous second derivative.
 Moreover, the symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}\leftrightarrow q_{2}$
\end_inset

 breaks in the phase corresponding to the first line in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD-1"

\end_inset

).
 A
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

similar phenomenon arises in UD of more than two pure states
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bergou2012"

\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has been argued above that cloning by discrimination is strictly suboptimal
 (unless 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

).
 One could likewise wonder if discrimination by cloning can be optimal.
 On heuristic grounds, one should not expect this to be so, as cloning involves
 a measurement and some information can be drawn from the observed outcome.
 However, the equal-prior and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\to0$
\end_inset

 cases provide remarkable exceptions.
 For both we may write the total failure rate as 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm C}}+(1-Q_{{\rm C}})Q_{{\rm UD}}$
\end_inset

, where C stands for cloning.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=1/2$
\end_inset

, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Q's"

\end_inset

) implies 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm C}}=Q_{-1}$
\end_inset

, in which case the produced 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-clone states are equally likely.
 The UD of these states fails with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{n}$
\end_inset

, as follows from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD-1"

\end_inset

) applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 copies.
 The total failure rate is then 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{m}$
\end_inset

, which is the optimal UD failure rate of the original input states, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD-1"

\end_inset

).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\to0$
\end_inset

 then only 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}^{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is produced with non-vanishing probability and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm C}}=Q_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Failure in the second step (UD) is given by the top line in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD-1"

\end_inset

) applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 copies.
 The total failure rate is 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2m}$
\end_inset

, also achieving optimality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using our main result in Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "main"

\end_inset

), and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "par sqrt"

\end_inset

) one can check that these are the only cases where discrimination by cloning
 is optimal.
 These are also the only cases where no information gain can be drawn from
 the cloning measurement.
 This hints at how special these cases are and justifies the need of the
 derived solution for arbitrary priors to have a full account of two-state
 cloning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Unequal priors II
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we show a different geometric/numeric solution using the
 Lagrange multipliers method with the constraint given in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:clone overlap"

\end_inset

), 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\sqrt{(1-q_{1})(1-q_{2})}s^{2}+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}},\label{eq:1 to 2 cloning constraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we set 
\begin_inset Formula $M=1,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

 for notation simplicity.
 This corresponds to one to two cloning but can be easily generalized for
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 cloning, 
\begin_inset Formula $M\geq N$
\end_inset

 .
 The function to be maximized is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{S}=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}+\lambda\left[s-\sqrt{\left(1-q_{1}\right)\left(1-q_{2}\right)}s^{2}-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the Lagrange multiplier to be determined which optimizes the failure
 rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}.$
\end_inset

 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial F/\partial q_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{2\eta_{1}}{\lambda} & = & \sqrt{\frac{q_{2}}{q_{1}}}-\sqrt{\frac{1-q_{2}}{1-q_{1}}}s^{2},\label{eq:lagr1}\\
\frac{2\eta_{2}}{\lambda} & = & \sqrt{\frac{q_{1}}{q_{2}}}-\sqrt{\frac{1-q_{1}}{1-q_{2}}}s^{2}.\label{eq:lagr2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\equiv\sqrt{\frac{q_{2}(1-q_{1})}{q_{1}(1-q_{2})}},$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\sqrt{\frac{q_{1}}{q_{2}}} & = & \frac{\lambda}{2\eta_{1}}\left[1-\frac{s^{2}}{A}\right],\\
\sqrt{\frac{q_{2}}{q_{1}}} & = & \frac{\lambda}{2\eta_{2}}\left[1-As^{2}\right],
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Multiplying the above two equations, setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\frac{4\eta\eta_{2}}{\lambda^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\frac{s^{4}-\delta+1}{s^{2}}$
\end_inset

 results in a quadratic equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\delta-1 & = & s^{2}\left[s^{2}-A-\frac{1}{A}\right],\nonumber \\
0 & = & A^{2}-CA+1.\label{eq:QuadratinA1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

It is the quadratic equation in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:QuadratinA1"

\end_inset

) with the combination of a second emerging quadratic equation we will use
 to obtain the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another quadratic equation emerges using the two equations in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagr1"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagr2"

\end_inset

).
 First let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\equiv\frac{\lambda}{2\eta_{1}}[1-\frac{s^{2}}{A}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\alpha}=\frac{\lambda}{2\eta_{2}}[1-As^{2}]$
\end_inset

 the relationship between the two failure rates becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sqrt{q_{1}}=\alpha\sqrt{q_{2}}.\label{eq:q12}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Using the relationship in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:q12"

\end_inset

) and the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed explicitly in terms of the fixed constants: 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\eta_{1},\eta_{2},s\}$
\end_inset

 and the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 which is yet to be determined.
 The derivation starts from the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $A,$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
A^{2} & = & \frac{q_{2}\left(1-q_{1}\right)}{q_{1}\left(1-q_{2}\right)},\\
\frac{q_{1}}{1-q_{1}}A^{2} & = & \frac{q_{2}}{1-q_{2}},\\
\frac{\alpha^{2}q_{2}}{1-\alpha^{2}q_{2}}A^{2} & = & \frac{q_{2}}{1-q_{2}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 then using the relationship 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=\alpha^{2}q_{2}$
\end_inset

 we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
q_{2} & = & \frac{1-\alpha^{2}A^{2}}{\alpha^{2}\left(1-A^{2}\right)},\\
q_{1} & = & \frac{1-\alpha^{2}A^{2}}{\left(1-A^{2}\right)}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

This is the expression of the individual failure rates which are yet to
 be optimized subject to the constraint.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 is replaced in the constraint given in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1 to 2 cloning constraint"

\end_inset

) and from there the optimal value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 can be obtained.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some prior calculations before replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 into the constraint will simplify the overall algebra:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-q_{1}=\frac{A^{2}\left(\alpha^{2}-1\right)}{\left(1-A^{2}\right)},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-q_{2}=\frac{\alpha^{2}-1}{\alpha^{2}\left(1-A^{2}\right)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we are ready to replace 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1-q_{i}$
\end_inset

 into the constraint (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1 to 2 cloning constraint"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
s & = & \frac{A\left(\alpha^{2}-1\right)}{\alpha\left(1-A^{2}\right)}s^{2}+\frac{1-\alpha^{2}A^{2}}{\alpha\left(1-A^{2}\right)},\\
\left(1-A^{2}\right)s & = & \frac{1}{\alpha}\left(1-s^{2}A^{2}\right)-\alpha A^{2}\left(1-\frac{s^{2}}{A}\right),\\
\left(1-A^{2}\right)s & = & \frac{\lambda}{2\eta_{2}}\left(1-s^{2}A^{2}\right)^{2}-\frac{\lambda A^{2}}{2\eta_{1}}\left(1-\frac{s^{2}}{A}\right)^{2}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Here we replaced 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{ \alpha=\frac{\lambda}{2\eta_{1}}\left[1-\frac{s^{2}}{A}\right] and \frac{1}{\alpha}=\frac{\lambda}{2\eta_{2}}\left[1-As^{2}\right]}.$
\end_inset

 After some trivial algebra the second quadratic equation in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 emerges:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A^{2}-\frac{2s^{2}(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})}{\eta_{1}s^{4}-\eta_{2}+2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s/\lambda}A+\frac{\eta_{1}-\eta_{2}s^{4}+2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s/\lambda}{\eta_{1}s^{4}-\eta_{2}+2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s/\lambda}=0\label{eq: 2nd quadratic in A}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The combination of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:QuadratinA1"

\end_inset

) and Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: 2nd quadratic in A"

\end_inset

) should give the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 which in turn gives explicit solution to the minimum individual failure
 rates, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i},$
\end_inset

 and overall optimal failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}.$
\end_inset

 Analytically such a solution is hard to achieve as one would have to solve
 a sixth order equation.
 Simply by plotting the two quadratic equations as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 the solution can be obtained at the intersection of the two graphs.
 There will be multiple intersections, hence multiple values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda.$
\end_inset

 The one which gives the lowest value of the overall failure rate is chosen.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/ashehu/Desktop/intersect(A1, A2).jpg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Enter some graphs from mathematica for some specific values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\eta_{1},\eta_{2},s\}$
\end_inset

 where the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 can be read off
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our future work we would like to obtain a closed form solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}.$
\end_inset

 One approach could be by making some educated guess for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Exact Cloning then Unambiguous Discrimination.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is interesting to see the connection between cloning and state discrimination
 of non-orthogonal quantum states.
 To get a better understanding we consider the two step process where we
 first clone then make a measurement.
 The other way around, state discrimination first then cloning is less interesti
ng because once we have succeeded in discriminating a state we can make
 as many copies as we wish by simply preparing them with the knowledge we
 get from the discrimination step.
 Making a clone first and then performing state discrimination gives some
 interesting results.
 For the case when the incoming states are prepared with equal priors we
 show that cloning first then performing UD on the cloned states which come
 with some new a priori probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

 the overall failure rate reaches the IDP limit.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea of the two step process is the following: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Probabilistic Exact Cloning: Given an ensemble of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 quantum states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 produce 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 exact clones while allowing for a rate of inconclusive outcomes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Unambiguous Discrimination: Perform optimal unambiguous discrimination on
 the successfully cloned states only, throwing away the failed states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Equal priors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Probabilistic Exact Cloning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We showed in Section (3.2.1) that for equal priors and a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 copies of two non-orthogonal states we could successfully produce exact
 copies with a probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{clone}=\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}}.$
\end_inset

 The average failure rate, failing to clone a state is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{clone}=1-P_{clone}=\frac{s^{M}-s^{N}}{1-s^{N}}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Optimal Unambiguous Discrimination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the input states are sent through the deterministic exact cloning
 machines, 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 states of of the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,\thinspace|\psi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 come out through the output port.
 The cloning machine only makes copies and does not say which state it has
 made a copy of.
 The clones are now sent through an unambiguous discriminating machine to
 distinguish the incoming states.
 Each of the states comes with a probability 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $P_{clone}=\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The incoming states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}^{N}\rangle_{s},|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle_{s}\}$
\end_inset

 which live in the state Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 are embedded with the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|i\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 which live in the ancilla Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $A.$
\end_inset

 Now the system and the ancilla live in the larger Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H=S\varotimes A.$
\end_inset

 The incoming states in this larger Hilbert space can be written in the
 product form 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}^{N}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a},|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a}\}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle^{\oplus N}\ket 0 & = & \sqrt{p}|\phi\rangle_{s}|1\rangle_{a}+\sqrt{q}|\Phi\rangle_{s}|0\rangle_{a}\nonumber \\
U|\psi_{1}\rangle^{\oplus N}\ket 0 & = & \sqrt{p}|\phi^{\perp}\rangle_{s}|2\rangle_{a}+\sqrt{q}|\Phi\rangle_{s}|0\rangle_{a}\label{eq:sep}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the probability of successfully discriminating the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}^{N}\rangle_{s}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is the probability of failing to discriminate 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}^{N}\rangle_{s},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p+q=1.$
\end_inset

 The unitary operator takes the two incoming states and projects them onto
 a pair of orthogonal states with some success and some failure probability.
 When there is a click on the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 the input states have been separated and output states 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi'_{i}\rangle_{s}$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal and thus fully distinguishable.
 If there is a click along the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 the incoming states have been collapsed into a single state which carries
 no information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product of the two equations in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sep"

\end_inset

) produces the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{N}=q.$
\end_inset

 In addition one has to take into consideration the fact that the states
 come in with a priori probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}p=\frac{1}{2}\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}}$
\end_inset

.
 The optimal inconclusive rate for discriminating the incoming pair of states
 is
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\tilde{\eta}_{1}q_{1}+\tilde{\eta}_{2}q_{2}=\eta_{1}p_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}q_{2}=\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}}s^{N}$
\end_inset

 , where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=q_{2}=s^{N}$
\end_inset

 and success rate is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=p_{2}=\frac{s^{M}-s^{N}}{1-s^{N}}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total inconclusive rate for the two step process, the failure rate to
 clone plus failure rate to unambiguously discriminate, is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Q_{total} & = & Q_{clone}+\left(1-Q_{clone}\right)Q_{UD},\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{s^{M}-s^{N}}{1-s^{N}}+\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}}s^{N}=s^{M}.\label{eq:overlap}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two step process reaches the IDP limit for optimal UD of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 non-orthogonal states.
 This is a special case and only occurs for symmetric case when states are
 prepared with equal prior probabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
State Separation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Exact Cloning one prepares perfect clones of the input states while allowing
 for some failure rate in which case no clones have been produced and the
 states are discarded.
 In optimal unambiguous discrimination (UD) the input states are made orthogonal
 and hence fully distinguishable.
 It was shown by Chefles and Barnett 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chefles1998a"

\end_inset

 that these strategies are a special case of a more general scheme.
 Both have two outcomes: failure and success.
 In each strategy the overlap of the input states is decreased, in UD the
 overlap becomes zero, in exact cloning it is the overlap of the input states
 raised to the power of the desired number of the clones to be made, 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{N}$
\end_inset

.
 State separation unifies the two schemes as it produces states with an
 overlap 
\begin_inset Formula $s'$
\end_inset

 in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq s'\leq s^{N}$
\end_inset

 while allowing for a fixed rate of inconclusive results.
 The authors showed the results for the case when the states are prepared
 with equal a priori probabilities.
 Complimentary of our recent work on probabilistic exact cloning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "yerokhin"

\end_inset

 where a geometric picture emerges we use similar tools to solve the more
 general state separation when the input states are prepared with different
 a priori probabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We approach state separation via the Neumark formulation.
 The system is embedded in a larger Hilbert space where the extra degrees
 of freedom are customarily called the ancilla.
 Then a unitary transformation entangles the system degrees of freedom with
 those of the ancilla.
 The input states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s},|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}\}$
\end_inset

 which live in the state Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{S}$
\end_inset

 are embedded with the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|i\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 which live in the Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{A}.$
\end_inset

 Now the system and the ancilla live in the larger Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H=H_{S}\varotimes H_{A}.$
\end_inset

 The incoming states in this larger Hilbert space can be written in the
 product form 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a},\thinspace|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a}\}.$
\end_inset

 The unitary should do the following: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\phi_{1}\rangle|\alpha\rangle+\sqrt{q_{1}}|\Phi_{o}\rangle|f\rangle,\nonumber \\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{2}}|\phi_{2}\rangle|\alpha\rangle+\sqrt{q_{2}}|\Phi_{o}\rangle|f\rangle,\label{eq:separation}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket f$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal.
 A projective measurement along the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 means that the states have successfully become more distinguishable with
 a success rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

, otherwise a measurement along the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket f$
\end_inset

 space means that the process has failed to produce more distinguishable
 states and the states are discarded with a probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}.$
\end_inset

 The separation of the input states is shown in Figure.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:state_separation"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product of the two equations in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation"

\end_inset

 gives the unitarity constraint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}s'+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}},\label{eq:separation constraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s=|\braket{\psi_{1}}{\psi_{2}}|^{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s'=|\braket{\phi_{1}}{\phi_{2}}|^{N}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For given 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 and average failure probability 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, we wish to find out the minimum value of the final overlap 
\begin_inset Formula $s'$
\end_inset

 as a function of the initial overlap
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 We could also look at the problem from a different angle: for a fixed value
 of the overlap of the output states what is the minimum value of failure
 rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 to achieve the desired separation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename state_separation.pdf
	width 8.5cm
	height 8.5cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The input states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}},\ket{\psi_{2}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are separated into a pair of more orthogonal states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\phi_{1}},\ket{\phi_{2}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 which are more distinguishable.
 
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space \hspace{}
\length 1cm
\end_inset

State separation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:state_separation"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
State Separation: equal priors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chefles and Barnett 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chefles1998a"

\end_inset

 solve the problem of equal priors employing Kraus representation of quantum
 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \hat{A},\hat{A}^{\dagger}\right\} .$
\end_inset

 However the solution is more straightforward using the Neumark setup in
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation"

\end_inset

).
 When the input states are prepared with equal priors 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2},$
\end_inset

 the solution is directly derived from the constraint in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation constraint"

\end_inset

) and no further optimization is necessary:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
s & = & ps'+q,\nonumber \\
p & = & \frac{1-s}{1-s'}.\label{eq:separation-1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now show applications of state separation to exact cloning and unambiguo
us state discrimination.
 Another application to state separation for equal priors is in hybrid cloning,
 see Section (3.6.1).
 Let us begin by showing the connection to exact cloning with failure rate.
 Suppose we are given a quantum system in either of the pure states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}},\ket{\psi_{2}}\right\} $
\end_inset

, such that the two states are non-orthogonal.
 The task is to produce two perfect copies of the input state.
 Let us embed the quantum system with a blank state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket i$
\end_inset

 so the system becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}}\ket i,\ket{\psi_{2}}\ket i\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 A perfect copying machine should produce 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}}\ket{\psi_{1}},\ket{\psi_{2}}\ket{\psi_{2}}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 A modified Neumark setup from state separation in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation"

\end_inset

) for cloning is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p}\ket{\psi_{1}}\ket{\psi_{1}}\ket{\alpha}+\sqrt{q}|\Phi_{o}\rangle|f\rangle,\nonumber \\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p}\ket{\psi_{1}}\ket{\psi_{1}}\ket{\alpha}+\sqrt{q}|\Phi_{o}\rangle|f\rangle,\label{eq:cloning}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product gives the unitarity constraint which is enough to fully
 solve the problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
s & = & ps^{2}+q\nonumber \\
p & = & \frac{1-s}{1-s^{2}}=\frac{1}{1+s}\label{eq:cloning-1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We notice that the success probability of producing two perfect clones with
 a rate of abstention (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cloning-1"

\end_inset

) could be derived from state separation success rate in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation-1"

\end_inset

) by replacing the overlap of output states 
\begin_inset Formula $s'$
\end_inset

 with the square overlap of input states 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that the Duan-Guo limit 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duan1998"

\end_inset

 is a special case of state separation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, state separation can be modified to produce 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 copies of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}},\ket{\psi_{2}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 initial copies, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N\geq M$
\end_inset

.
 We derived the solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 cloning in section (3.2.1).
 It could simply be derived from Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation-1"

\end_inset

) replacing the overlap of input states 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{M}$
\end_inset

, the overlap of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 states, and 
\begin_inset Formula $s'$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{N},$
\end_inset

 the overlap of the clones.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
State separation also reproduces the IDP limit in state discrimination for
 the case when the states are prepared with arbitrary priors.
 Simply setting the overlap of the output states to zero 
\begin_inset Formula $s'=0$
\end_inset

, so that the states have been separated and are fully distinguishable,
 produces the IDP limit 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1-s$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
State Separation: unequal priors 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now seek to generalize the results of state separation to the case when
 the possible input states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}},\ket{\psi_{2}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are prepared with different a priori probabilities.
 All the symmetries enjoyed for equal priors break down and in order to
 obtain a fully analytical solution one would have to solve a sixth order
 equation.
 Instead we resort to solving the problem geometrically as the solution
 turns out to be more insightful.
 The Neumark setup is shown in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation"

\end_inset

) and the constraint in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation constraint"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We resort to the parametrization of the probabilities giving the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $(s,\min s')$
\end_inset

 in parametric form, rather than attempting to give min 
\begin_inset Formula $s'$
\end_inset

 as an explicit function of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, which would require solving a high degree polynomial equation.
 We choose a change of variables which linearizes the unitarity constraint
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation constraint"

\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{1}p_{1}=t^{2},\quad q_{1}q_{2}=z^{2}.\label{eb cha qs -> z & t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The condition becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z=s-s't,\qquad0\le t,z\le1,\qquad0\le s'\le s.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is a straight line in the first quadrant of the plane 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 with negative slope
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $-s'$
\end_inset

 and crossing the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-axis at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=s$
\end_inset

.
 From the first equation in 
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eb cha qs -> z & t"

\end_inset

) we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t^{2}=(1-q_{1})(1-q_{2})=1+z^{2}-q_{1}-q_{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 and substituting back in the second equation in 
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eb cha qs -> z & t"

\end_inset

) we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{1}(q_{1}-1+t^{2}-z^{2})+z^{2}=0.
\]

\end_inset

We now solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{1}=\frac{1+z^{2}-t^{2}\pm\sqrt{(1+z^{2}-t^{2})^{2}-4z^{2}}}{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Similarly, for 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{2}=\frac{1+z^{2}-t^{2}\mp\sqrt{(1+z^{2}-t^{2})^{2}-4z^{2}}}{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore, the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}$
\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2Q=1+z^{2}-t^{2}\pm(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\sqrt{(1+z^{2}-t^{2})^{2}-4z^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

We now solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 After a bit of algebra we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
z^{2} & = & \frac{2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(1+\tau)-1+Q+\sqrt{\left(1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\right)\left[(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\tau\right]}}{2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}\\
 & \equiv & \zeta(\tau)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\equiv t^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{2}$
\end_inset

 cannot be less than zero, we picked up the plus sign for the root.
 Let us assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le\eta_{1}\le1/2$
\end_inset

 to simplify the analysis.
 We need to locate the maximum of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 For that, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dz}{dt}=\frac{d\sqrt{\zeta}}{d\tau}2t=\frac{d\zeta}{d\tau}\frac{t}{z}.
\]

\end_inset

The derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $d\zeta/d\tau$
\end_inset

 is immediate.
 We find that the maximum is located at 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t_{{\rm min}}=\left\{ \begin{array}{lll}
{\displaystyle \sqrt{\left(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{1}}\right)\left(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{2}}\right)},\quad} & {\rm if} & \quad0\le Q\le2\eta_{1}\\[2em]
0,\quad & {\rm if} & \quad2\eta_{1}<Q\le1.
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset

The corresponding values of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{{\rm min}}=\left\{ \begin{array}{lll}
{\displaystyle \frac{Q}{2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}},\quad} & {\rm if} & \quad0\le Q\le2\eta_{1}\\[2em]
{\displaystyle \sqrt{\frac{Q-\eta_{1}}{\eta_{2}}},\quad} & {\rm if} & \quad2\eta_{1}<Q\le1.
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset

There is a second point that we need to define.
 We first note that for equal priors the curve is simply the hyperbola 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z^{2}=t^{2}+2Q-1,
\]

\end_inset

which intersects the straight line 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z=1-t
\]

\end_inset

at the point 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(z,t\right)=\left(Q,1-Q\right).
\]

\end_inset

By trying this solution in 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{2}=\zeta(t^{2})$
\end_inset

 we note that it is actually a general solution for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, the straight line 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1-t$
\end_inset

 is tangent to
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $z^{2}=\zeta(t^{2})$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $(Q,1-Q)$
\end_inset

 for any values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, as can be checked by substituting in the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $dz/dt=(t/z)(d\zeta/d\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Note also that 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1-t$
\end_inset

 is the limiting line for the family 
\begin_inset Formula $z=s-s't$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, an obvious parametrization for the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $(s,s')$
\end_inset

 is obtained as follows: 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 i
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s'(t)=-\frac{dz}{dt}=-\frac{t\,\zeta'(t^{2})}{\sqrt{\zeta(t^{2})}},\qquad t_{{\rm min}}\le t\le1-Q,
\]

\end_inset

and next 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ii
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s(t)=z+ts'(t)=\sqrt{\zeta(t^{2})}+ts'(t),\qquad t_{{\rm min}}\le t\le1-Q,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\zeta'(\tau)=1-\frac{\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\tau}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $s<z_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 it is always possible to separate the initial states, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 can be made orthogonal.
 We note that the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $s=z_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the unambiguous discrimination result 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q=2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s,\quad Q=\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}s^{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Separation1.graph.pdf
	width 8.5cm
	height 8.5cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space \hspace{}
\length 1cm
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $s'$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The plot is for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=0.1$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 the curves approach a straight line.
 The difference is more noticeable for very small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "s' vs s"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Deterministic State Dependent Quantum Cloning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we derive the works of Chefles and Barnett 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chefles1999"

\end_inset

 in designing an approximate quantum cloning machine for two possible input
 states while maximizing the global fidelity.
 Consider a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 non-orthogonal quantum states with 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 copies each 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle^{\otimes M}=|\psi_{i}\rangle|\psi_{i}\rangle...|\psi_{i}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 The states are unknown and our task is to produce 
\begin_inset Formula $N>M$
\end_inset

 copies, as best as we can.
 Introducing an ancilla state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\chi\rangle$
\end_inset

 which is 
\begin_inset Formula $N-M$
\end_inset

 dimensional the goal is to transform the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{j}\rangle|\chi\rangle$
\end_inset

 into the state which approximates the N exact copies of the input state
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{j}^{N}\rangle.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is deterministic cloning, although imperfect, clones are generated
 on demand.
 The authors choose the global fidelity rate to improve the quality of the
 clones so they resemble the given copies as closely as possible.
 This measure was introduced by Bruss et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bruss1998"

\end_inset

.
 Thus given a set 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of non orthogonal states 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phi_{j}^{N}}=|\psi_{i}\rangle^{\otimes M},$
\end_inset

 we wish to produce a set 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 clones 
\begin_inset Formula $|\phi_{j}\rangle^{\otimes N}$
\end_inset

 while optimizing the global fidelity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{MN}=\sum_{j=1}^{K}\eta_{j}|\langle\psi_{j}^{N}|\phi_{j}^{N}\rangle|^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other figures of merit can also be used to improve the quality of the clones,
 such as local fidelity.
 The local fidelity is the average fidelity of each of the individual clones
 of each of the N subsystems measured against the input states 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{j}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 The authors choose the global fidelity due to its close connection to state
 discrimination.
 We are also very interested in the connection between cloning and state
 discrimination, particularly in the two step process where clones are first
 produced then the clones are unambiguously discriminated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The global fidelity can be expressed differently if unitary operator acts
 on the input states 
\begin_inset Formula $U|\psi_{j}^{M}\rangle|\chi\rangle=|\phi_{j}^{N}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{MN}=\sum_{j=1}^{K}\eta_{j}|\langle\psi_{j}^{N}|U|\psi_{j}^{M}\rangle|\chi\rangle|^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem of maximizing the fidelity can be explicitly solved for a set
 of two possible input states 
\begin_inset Formula $K=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}.$
\end_inset

 It was originally solved by Bruss 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bruss1998"

\end_inset

 for the case when the the incoming states are prepared with equal a priori
 probabilities.
 They noticed that the optimum clones 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\Phi_{1}\rangle,|\Phi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 lie in the subspace spanned by the input states to be cloned 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A unitary produces 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 copies 
\begin_inset Formula $|\phi_{1}^{N}\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\phi_{2}^{N}\rangle,$
\end_inset

 to resemble the original states as best as possible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}^{M}\rangle|i\rangle & = & |\phi_{1}^{N}\rangle\\
U|\psi_{2}^{M}\rangle|i\rangle & = & |\phi_{2}^{N}\rangle
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product of the above two equations gives a relationship between
 the input and the output states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{M} & = & |\langle\phi_{1}|\phi_{2}\rangle|^{N},\\
s^{M} & = & s'^{N},\label{eq:3.4.6}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{M=}|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s'^{N}=|\langle\phi_{1}|\phi_{2}\rangle|$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The input states can be expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
|\psi_{1}\rangle & = & \cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|0\rangle,\nonumber \\
|\psi_{2}\rangle & = & \cos\theta|1\rangle-\sin\theta|0\rangle,
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
similarly the clones yet to be optimized can be expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
|\phi_{1}\rangle & = & \cos\phi_{1}|1\rangle+\sin\phi_{1}|0\rangle,\nonumber \\
|\phi_{2}\rangle & = & \cos\phi_{2}|1\rangle-\sin\phi_{2}|0\rangle.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using this general representation of input and output states and using the
 overlap relation in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3.4.6"

\end_inset

 we see that the sum of the output angles is fixed as 
\begin_inset Formula $|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{M}=\cos^{M}2\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\langle\phi_{1}|\phi_{2}\rangle|^{N}=\cos^{N}(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2})\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos^{M}2\theta=\cos^{N}(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The global fidelity in terms of the angles becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{MN} & = & \eta_{1}|\left|\langle\psi_{1}|\phi_{1}\rangle\right|+\eta_{2}\left|\langle\psi_{2}|\phi_{2}\rangle\right|^{2},\\
 & = & \eta_{1}\left(\cos\theta\cos\phi_{1}+\sin\theta\sin\phi_{1}\right)+\eta_{2}\left(\cos\theta\cos\phi_{2}+\sin\theta\sin\phi_{2}\right),\nonumber \\
 & = & \eta_{1}\cos^{2}\left(\theta-\phi_{1}\right)+\eta_{2}\cos^{2}\left(\theta-\phi_{2}\right).
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rewriting the fidelity in terms of the sum and difference of the output
 angles, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{MN} & = & \eta_{1}\cos^{2}\left(\theta-\frac{\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}}{2}-\frac{\phi_{1}-\phi_{2}}{2}\right)+\eta_{2}\cos^{2}\left(\theta-\frac{\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}}{2}+\frac{\phi_{1}-\phi_{2}}{2}\right),\nonumber \\
 & = & \eta_{1}\cos^{2}\left(\alpha-x\right)+\eta_{2}\cos^{2}\left(\alpha+x\right),\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[\eta_{1}\left(\cos2(\alpha-x)+1\right)]+\frac{1}{2}[\eta_{2}\left(\cos2(\alpha+x)+1\right)\right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\eta_{1}(\cos2(\alpha-x)+\eta_{2}(\cos2(\alpha+x)\right],
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\theta-\frac{\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}}{2}$
\end_inset

 is fixed and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{\phi_{1}-\phi_{2}}{2}$
\end_inset

 is the only variable subject to optimization.
 Differentiating with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\eta_{1}\sin(\alpha-x) & = & \eta_{2}\sin(\alpha-x)\nonumber \\
\eta_{1}\left[\sin2\alpha\cos2x-\cos2\alpha\cos2x\right] & = & \eta_{2}\left[\sin2\alpha\cos2x+\cos2\alpha\cos2x\right]\nonumber \\
(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\sin2\alpha\cos2x & = & \cos2\alpha\cos2x\nonumber \\
\left(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2}\right)\tan2\alpha & = & \tan2x\label{eq:tan2x}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
This is the relationship that gives the optimal clones and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 should be replaced in 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{MN}$
\end_inset

.
 To be able to use this relationship we re-express 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{MN}$
\end_inset

 in a different way: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\eta_{1}\cos2(\alpha-x)+\eta_{2}\cos2(\alpha+x)\right],\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[\cos2\alpha\cos2x\left\{ 1+(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\tan2\alpha\tan2x\right\} \right]+\frac{1}{2},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 we can rewrite (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:tan2x"

\end_inset

) as 
\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\tan2\alpha=\frac{\sin2x}{\cos2x}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\thinspace\cos2x=\frac{\sqrt{1-\cos^{2}2x}}{(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\tan2\alpha}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})^{2}\tan^{2}(2\alpha)}}.$
\end_inset

 Finally the optimal fidelity can be expressed in terms of the a-priori
 probabilities and the overlap of the input states only .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\cos2\alpha\cos2x\left\{ 1+\left(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2}\right)\tan2\alpha\tan2x\right\} \right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\frac{\cos2\alpha}{\sqrt{1+\left(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2}\right)^{2}\tan^{2}(2\alpha)}}\{1+\left(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2}\right)^{2}\tan^{2}2\alpha\right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\cos2\alpha\sqrt{1+\left(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2}\right)^{2}\tan^{2}2\alpha}\right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\sqrt{\cos^{2}2\alpha+\left(1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\right)\sin^{2}2\alpha}\right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin^{2}2\alpha}\right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin^{2}\left(2\theta-\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\right)}\right].\label{eq:fid}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the asymptotic limit, producing infinitely many copies 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, fidelity merges into the Helstrom bound in the discrimination of non-orthogona
l pure states.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos2\theta=s^{M}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2})=s^{N}$
\end_inset

 and expanding the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin$
\end_inset

 term under the square root, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sin\left(2\theta-\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\right) & = & \sin2\theta\cos\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)-\cos2\theta\sin\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\\
 & = & \sqrt{1-\cos^{2}(2\theta)}\cos\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)-\cos2\theta\sin\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\\
 & = & \sqrt{1-s^{2M}}s^{N}-s^{M}\sqrt{1-s^{2N}}\\
 & = & -s^{M}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting back into Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fid"

\end_inset

) Helstrom bound emerges: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{M∞}=\frac{1}{2}[1+\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\cos^{2}(2\theta)}]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the mathematics shows the convergence of Fidelity into optimal minimum
 error state discrimination it is not clear as to why this connection should
 exist at all.
 On the one hand fidelity optimizes the average overlap between the clones
 and input states while ME state discrimination minimizes the error rate
 of failing to distinguish the incoming state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will show the connection in the following two step process: first measure
 and prepare then optimize the fidelity rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Step 1: Measure and prepare
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Discriminate the incoming states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}^{M}},\ket{\psi_{2}^{M}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with optimal ME then prepare states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}^{N}},\ket{\psi_{2}^{N}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with the corresponding probabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}^{M}\rangle|0\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\psi_{1}^{N}\rangle|1\rangle+\sqrt{r_{1}}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|2\rangle,\\
U|\psi_{2}^{M}\rangle|0\rangle & = & \sqrt{r_{2}}|\psi_{1}^{N}\rangle|1\rangle+\sqrt{p_{2}}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|2\rangle,
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{i}^{M}}$
\end_inset

 is received we successfully prepare the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{i}^{N}}$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 and mistakenly prepare the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{j}^{N}}$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Step 2: Optimize the fidelity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The global fidelity for state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}^{N}}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{1} & = & p_{1}|\braket{\psi_{1}}{\psi_{1}}|^{N}+r_{1}|\braket{\psi_{2}}{\psi_{1}}|^{2N},\\
 & = & p_{1}+r_{1}|\braket{\psi_{2}}{\psi_{1}}|^{2N}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly for state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}^{N}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{2}=p_{2}+r_{2}|\braket{\psi_{1}}{\psi_{2}}|^{2N}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The average fidelity for both states is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{MN} & = & \eta_{1}F_{1}+\eta_{2}F_{2}\nonumber \\
 & = & \eta_{1}\left(p_{1}+r_{1}|\braket{\psi_{2}}{\psi_{1}}|^{2N}\right)+\eta_{2}\left(p_{2}+r_{2}|\braket{\psi_{1}}{\psi_{2}}|^{2N}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \eta_{1}p_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}+\eta_{1}r_{1}s^{2N}+\eta_{2}r_{2}s^{2N}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is now clear that in the asymptotic limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 fidelity reproduces the Helstrom bound 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{MN}=\eta_{1}p_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}.$
\end_inset

 However the relationship between optimal fidelity and optimal state discriminat
ion for a finite number of copies 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 remains an open question.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hybrid Cloning: Interpolation between exact and approximate cloning 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we seek to interpolate between probabilistic exact cloning
 and approximate cloning machines using our results from state separation.
 Exact cloning machines produce perfect clones while allowing for some inconclus
ive outcomes.
 Approximate cloning machines produce copies on demand which resemble the
 input states by maximizing the fidelity.
 One can imagine a scheme where fidelity can be higher then maximum fidelity
 in the approximate cloning machine while it allows for a fixed rate of
 inconclusive outcomes, FRIO.
 This scheme should reproduce exact cloning and approximate cloning machines
 by setting FRIO to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 and zero respectively.
 Chefles and Barnett 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chefles1999"

\end_inset

 solved the problem for the case when the input states are prepared with
 equal a priori probabilities.
 We extend the solution to the more general case when the states are prepared
 with different priors.
 Such a solution is possible due to our recent work on making 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 perfect clones from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 copies of one of two known pure states with minimum failure probability
 in the general case where the known states have arbitrary priori probabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equal priors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution to the interpolation of cloning for equal a priori probabilities
 has been derived by Chefles et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chefles1999"

\end_inset

.
 The authors develop a scheme which, depending on the fidelity of the clones,
 can interpolate between exact cloning with inconclusive results in one
 extreme and optimal approximate cloning on the other extreme.
 In our work this scheme has been generalized for the case when the input
 states are prepared with different a priori probabilities.
 First we show the derivation of the equal priors as it will help to better
 understand the general case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=1/2,$
\end_inset

 the output states are symmetric, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}=\phi_{2}=\phi,$
\end_inset

 and the optimal global fidelity, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{MN}$
\end_inset

, in Eq.(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fid"

\end_inset

) reduces to: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\sqrt{1-\sin^{2}\left(2\theta-2\phi\right)}\right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\cos^{2}\left(2\theta-2\phi\right)\right].\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Duan and Guo 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duan1998"

\end_inset

 showed that the maximum success probability of obtaining 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 exact clones from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 given copies of non-orthogonal quantum states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

, which are prepared with equal a priori probabilities, is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{MN}=\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the overlap of the input states 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 The success rate for 1 to 2 cloning, 
\begin_inset Formula $M=1,N=2,$
\end_inset

 reduces to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{12}=\frac{1}{1+s}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The interpolation takes us from optimal exact cloning to maximum fidelity.
 Given a set 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of two non-orthogonal quantum states, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 the goal is to make 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 clones 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\phi_{1}\rangle,|\phi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

, which are similar to the input states but not perfect.
 The Neumark setup is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle^{\otimes M}|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p}|\phi_{1}\rangle^{\oplus N}|1\rangle+\sqrt{q}|f\rangle|0\rangle\label{eq:NeumarkClone1}\\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle^{\oplus M}|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p}|\phi_{2}\rangle^{\oplus N}|1\rangle+\sqrt{q}|f\rangle|0\rangle\label{eq:NeumarkClone2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The input states are prepared with equal a priori probabilities.
 A click in the 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 direction means that we succeed in making the clones and the probability
 of success is 
\begin_inset Formula $p.$
\end_inset

 A click in the 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle$
\end_inset

 direction means that we failed to create a clone with a probability 
\begin_inset Formula $q.$
\end_inset

 The inner product or (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NeumarkClone1"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NeumarkClone2"

\end_inset

) gives the constraint: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s^{M}=ps'^{N}+q
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the unitarity condition 
\begin_inset Formula $p+q=1,$
\end_inset

 the average rate of successfully making a clone is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p=\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s'^{N}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $s'$
\end_inset

 is the overlap of the clones 
\begin_inset Formula $s'=\langle\phi_{1}|\phi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 If the final states are orthogonal, 
\begin_inset Formula $s'=0$
\end_inset

 then the state separation reaches the IDP limit and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{S}=P_{IDP}=1-|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{M}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we express the overlap of the output states in terms on the success
 rates and the overlap of input states,
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos2\theta=|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{N}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
|\langle\phi_{1}|\phi_{2}\rangle|^{N} & = & 1-\frac{1-|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{M}}{P_{S}}\\
\cos^{N}(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}) & = & 1-\frac{P_{IDP}}{P_{S}}\label{eq:seperation}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The exact clones live in an N dimensional space 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1,2}^{N}\rangle=\cos\theta|1\rangle\pm\sin\theta|0\rangle.$
\end_inset

 The approximate clones can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $|\phi_{1,2}\rangle=\cos\phi_{1}|1\rangle\pm\sin\phi_{1}|0\rangle$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fidelity rate for equal priors is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{MN}=\frac{1}{2}\left[1+\cos(2\theta-\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and we want to use the relationship in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seperation"

\end_inset

).
 Let us expand the cosine term 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(2\theta-\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\right)=\cos2\theta\cos\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)+\sin2\theta\sin\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fidelity becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\\
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+|\langle\psi_{1}^{N}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|\left(1-\frac{P_{IDP}}{P_{S}}\right)+\frac{1}{P_{S}}(\left(1-|\langle\psi_{1}^{N}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|^{2}\right)\left(P_{S}^{2}-\left(P_{S}-P_{IDP}\right)^{2}\right)^{1/2}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 As 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\infty,\thinspace|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{N}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{MN}$
\end_inset

 reduces to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{MN}=\frac{1}{2}[1+\frac{1}{P_{S}}\sqrt{P_{S}^{2}-(P_{S}-P_{IDP})^{2}}].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also express the fidelity in terms of fixed failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=1-P_{S}$
\end_inset

 which serves as the parameter by which we are interpolating and the optimal
 failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}=\left|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle\right|$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+|\langle\psi_{1}^{N}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|(1-\frac{1-Q_{o}}{1-Q})+\frac{1}{1-Q}(\left(1-|\langle\psi_{1}^{N}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|^{2}\right)\left(\left(1-Q\right)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}\right)^{1/2}\right],\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2\left(1-Q\right)}\left[(1-Q)+Q_{o}^{N}(Q_{o}-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q_{o}^{2N})\left[(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}\right]}\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

In the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\infty,\thinspace|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{N}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\frac{1}{1-Q}\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}\right],\\
(1-Q)F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[(1-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(1-Q)F_{MN}=P_{succes}$
\end_inset

, the probability of successfully identifying a state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{success} & = & \frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(This is a different success rate then the 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{S}$
\end_inset

 defined above, the 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{S}$
\end_inset

 was defined as the rate of successfully carrying out a state separation.
 )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This formula describes the relationship between the discrimination of states
 with a fixed rate of inconclusive outcome.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

 it reaches the Helstrom bound of minimum error and when 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 it reaches the IDP limit in UD.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
General case
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We would like to generalize the above results for the case when the incoming
 states are prepared with different prior probabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Step 1: State Separation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimally separate the incoming states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}^{M}},\ket{\psi_{2}^{M}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with a fixed rate of inconclusive results 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

, then prepare states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}^{N}},\ket{\psi_{2}^{N}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with the corresponding success probabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}^{M}\rangle|0\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\phi_{1}\rangle|1\rangle+\sqrt{q_{1}}|\Phi\rangle|2\rangle,\nonumber \\
U|\psi_{2}^{M}\rangle|0\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{2}}|\phi_{1}\rangle|1\rangle+\sqrt{q_{2}}|\Phi\rangle|2\rangle,
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The incoming states are separated with a success probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 and failed to separate the states with a failure probability 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The inner product of the two equations gives the unitarity constraint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}s'+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\label{eq:setaration constraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Step 2: Optimize Fidelity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fidelity for state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 is: 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}=\left|\braket{\psi_{1}^{N}}{\phi_{1}}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly the fidelity for state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\braket{\psi_{2}^{N}}{\phi_{2}}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The overall fidelity is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\frac{\eta_{1}p_{1}F_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}F_{2}}{\eta_{1}p_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}}=\frac{\eta_{1}p_{1}F_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}F_{2}}{1-Q}=\tilde{\eta}_{1}F_{1}+\tilde{\eta}_{2}F_{2},
\]

\end_inset

where the normalized a priori probabilities are 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\eta}_{i}=\frac{\eta_{i}p_{i}}{1-Q}$
\end_inset

.
 The average fidelity is the same as calculated in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fid"

\end_inset

) with the new normalized probabilities: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\sqrt{1-4\tilde{\eta}_{1}\tilde{\eta}_{2}\sin^{2}\left(2\theta-\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\right)}\right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2(1-Q)}\left[(1-Q)+\sqrt{\left(1-Q\right)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}p_{1}p_{2}\sin^{2}\left(2\theta-\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\right)}\right],
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be seen that in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, expanding the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin$
\end_inset

 term as we did in the previous section, the FRIO 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan2012"

\end_inset

 results are recovered.
 It again shows a close relationship between fidelity and state discrimination.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving the problem of hybrid cloning however requires one last optimization,
 that of the second term under the square root
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Lambda & = & \sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}\sin\left(2\theta-\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\right),\\
 & = & \sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}\sqrt{1-s^{2n}}s'-\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}(1-s'^{2}})s^{n}\\
 & = & \sqrt{1-s^{2n}}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)-s^{n}\sqrt{1-(q_{1}+q_{2})+q_{1}q_{2}-\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}},\\
 & = & \sqrt{1-s^{2n}}\left(s-u\right)-s^{n}\sqrt{1-s^{2}-2v+2sv}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $u\equiv\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}},\hspace{0.5cm}v\equiv\frac{1}{2}\left(q_{1}+q_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 and we used the constraint from the unitarity in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation constraint"

\end_inset

) to replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}s'=s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Experimental realization to FRIO
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Choosing a physical system to realize quantum information processes, which
 have otherwise been solved theoretically, is central challenge to building
 a quantum computer.
 Some of the systems in use today are: energy levels of ions, the orientation
 of nuclear spin, the presence or absence of a photon in a cavity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cirac1995,Gershenfeld1997,Turchette1995,Domokos1995"

\end_inset

 and dual rail representation of a qubit proposed by Milburn 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Milburn1989"

\end_inset

 and later by Chuang and Yamamoto 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chuang1996"

\end_inset

.
 We will realize the implementation of our works using the dual rail representat
ion of photons combined with a six-port, which is a linear device with three
 input and three output ports.
 The six-port can be realized with beamsplitters and phase shifters.
 First we will demonstrate the power and simplicity of this system by working
 out the implementation of UD following the work by Bergou 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bergou2009"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "shehu"

\end_inset

 we generalized the optical implementation schemes to state discrimination
 which optimally interpolates between UD and ME with a fixed rate of inconclusiv
e results FRIO.
 Ever since the interpolation scheme of a general measurement with FRIO
 was derived by Bagan 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan2012"

\end_inset

 there has been a quest for a physical realization.
 The authors solved the problem using an operator transformation technique
 that reformulated the intermediate problem into a ME problem with an extra
 optimization parameter.
 Essentially they reduced the problem from a three element POVM to two element
 POVM similar to ME.
 Inspired by the work of Reck and Zeilinger 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reck1994"

\end_inset

 in which they prove that any discreet finite dimensional unitary operator
 can be constructed in the lab as a multi-port interferometer using beamsplitter
s and phase shifters we set out to solve the FRIO using the Neumark setup
 as it lends itself into an optical implementation.
 This gives us a closed form solution as in Bagan 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al.$
\end_inset

 In addition it gives a three dimensional unitary operator where all the
 coefficients are explicitly calculated in terms of a priori probabilities,
 overlap of the input states and FRIO.
 Using the Reck 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al.$
\end_inset

 algorithm the unitary is decomposed in terms of beam splitters with correspondi
ng coefficients of transmittance and reflectivity.
 The setup reduces into the UD by setting the error rate to zero, in turn
 it reproduces the work of Bergou 
\begin_inset Formula $et\hspace{0.3cm}al$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bergou2009"

\end_inset

.
 At the other extreme it produces the setup to ME for FRIO equal to zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Analytical Solution of Interpolation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we solve the interpolation with FRIO in two different ways.
 In the first method, through a parametrization, the problem is converted
 into a minimum error whose solution is well known.
 Then there is one last optimization with respect to a FRIO.
 This method generates the same solution as in Bagan 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al$
\end_inset

 in a few lines.
 However to obtain an experimental realization we give an alternative solution
 using Neumark's theorem.
 It is a generalized measurement procedure in which the system is embedded
 in a larger Hilbert space with extra degrees of freedom.
 A unitary transformation entangles the system with the extra degree of
 freedom known as ancilla.
 After this interaction has taken place, projective von Neumann measurements
 are carried out on the ancilla.
 Our input states are qubits, which can be expressed in general as unit
 length vectors in the two dimensional basis spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|2\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 In the output of the transformation, we associate the basis state 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|2\rangle$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle$
\end_inset

 gives no information about the system.
 The unitary transformation should do the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|0\rangle_{a} & =\sqrt{p_{1}}|1\rangle_{s}\ket 1_{a}+\sqrt{r_{1}}|2\rangle_{s}\ket 2_{a}+\sqrt{q_{1}}|0\rangle_{s}\ket 0_{a},\nonumber \\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|0\rangle_{a} & =\sqrt{r_{2}}|1\rangle_{s}\ket 1_{a}+\sqrt{p_{2}}|2\rangle_{s}\ket 2_{a}+\sqrt{q_{2}}|0\rangle_{s}\ket 0_{a},\label{eq:frio constraint}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where: 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that state 
\begin_inset Formula $i\thinspace(i=1,2)$
\end_inset

 is correctly identified, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that the detector mistakenly identifies state 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the failure probability, the detector fails to identify the state at
 all.
 A click in the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 means the results are inconclusive and we learn nothing from the measurement.
 From the unitarity conditions we obtain the normalized probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}+r_{i}+q_{i}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We wish to maximize the probability of success, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}=\eta_{1}p_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}$
\end_inset

, and minimize the error rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}$
\end_inset

, for a fixed failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}.$
\end_inset

 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}+P_{e}+Q=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product of the two equations in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:frio constraint"

\end_inset

) gives the overlap of the input states in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i},\thinspace p_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}+\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}},\label{eq:general constraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s\equiv\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 This is a constraint on the optimization of ME with a FRIO.
 First we show the solution for the case when the input states are prepared
 with equal priors for which the problem is fully solved from the constraint.
 It was initially solved by Chefles and Barnett using a different approach
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chefles1998"

\end_inset

.
 Then we solve the general case for different priors and reproduce the results
 of Bagan 
\begin_inset Formula $et\thinspace al.$
\end_inset

 with two different methods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equal priors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first present the solution where the incoming states are given with
 equal a-priori probabilities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies equal error, success and failure rates: 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}=r_{2}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=p_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the total error and failure rates reduce to: 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}=r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}=q.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can immediately solve the constraint in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general constraint"

\end_inset

) by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1-r-Q$
\end_inset

, solving the quadratic equation for the error rate in terms of the failure
 rate and overlap 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, which is also the overall failure rate in the IDP limit for the equal
 priors: 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}\equiv2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s=s$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
s & = & \sqrt{pr}+\sqrt{pr}+Q,\nonumber \\
Q_{o} & = & 2\sqrt{r(1-r-Q)}+Q,\nonumber \\
(Q_{o}-Q)^{2} & = & 4r(1-r-Q),\nonumber \\
\frac{1}{4}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2} & = & r(1-Q)-r^{2},\nonumber \\
0 & = & r^{2}-(1-Q)r+\frac{1}{4}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}.\label{eq:quadratic IM}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Solving the quadratic equation and taking the smaller root, 
\begin_inset Formula $i.e$
\end_inset

 the smaller error rate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r=P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}],\\
p=P_{S}=\frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}].
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equal priors case requires no further optimization.
 Simply solving the quadratic equation in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:quadratic IM"

\end_inset

) derived from the constraint the optimal solution is carried out.
 By varying the failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 from zero to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 we recover the Helstrom and IDP bounds.
 In the Helstrom bound 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Helstrom1969"

\end_inset

 one is not allowed to have inconclusive results, hence setting failure
 rate to zero, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

 results in 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}[1-\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the IDP limit 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ivanovic1987,Dieks1988,Peres1988"

\end_inset

 where one is not allowed to make an error 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0,$
\end_inset

 while allowing for inconclusive outcomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
0 & = & \frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}],\\
Q & = & Q_{o},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 in the overlap of the input states for equal priors 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}=s.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Arbitrary priors 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of the recent interest in this problem, we feel it is beneficial
 to show two new and different approaches to its solution.
 The first is more conceptual: a renormalization inspired by E.
 Bagan et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan2012"

\end_inset

 allows us to rewrite the problem as a ME problem with an implicit dependence
 on the last free parameter, the failure rate of one state with relation
 to the other.
 This greatly simplifies the problem as the solution to the first part is
 well known and the second is a straight-forward derivative.
 The second solution employs a Lagrange multiplier method that is algebraically
 difficult but useful in its explicit results of individual error rates.
 This in turn is useful in designing an implementation scheme where the
 reflective and transmittance coefficients are expressed in terms of individual
 error and success rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Transformation of the problem into the Helstrom form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Through a renormalization our problem is converted into the well known Helstrom
 form the solution of which is well known.
 First we define the useful quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\equiv s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}$
\end_inset

 which will serve as normalized overlap and the unitarity constraint from
 Eq.(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general constraint"

\end_inset

) reduces to: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega=\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}+\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next we renormalize all probabilities in the problem: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \tilde{p}_{i}=\frac{p_{i}}{\alpha_{i}},\nonumber \\
 & \tilde{r_{i}}=\frac{r_{i}}{\alpha_{i}},\nonumber \\
 & \tilde{\omega}=\frac{\omega}{\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}},\\
\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}=1-q_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Now the probabilities are normalized 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{r}_{i}+\tilde{p}_{i}=1$
\end_inset

, and the new normalized overlap is in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{r_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{p}_{i},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\omega}=\sqrt{\tilde{p}_{1}\tilde{r}_{2}}+\sqrt{\tilde{p_{2}}\tilde{r}_{1}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the above transformation of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 the error rate can be expressed as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{P}_{E}=\tilde{\eta}_{1}\tilde{r}_{1}+\tilde{\eta}_{2}\tilde{r}_{2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{P}_{E}=\frac{P_{E}}{\eta_{1}\alpha_{1}+\eta_{2}\alpha_{2}}=\frac{P_{E}}{1-Q},\tilde{\eta}_{i}=\frac{\eta_{i}\alpha_{i}}{\eta_{1}\alpha_{1}+\eta_{2}\alpha_{2}}=\frac{\eta_{i}\alpha_{i}}{1-Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\eta}_{1}+\tilde{\eta}_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have transformed the problem into a discrimination between two pure states
 with overlap 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\omega}$
\end_inset

 and no explicit failure rate.
 Hence we can simply write down the expression for the minimum error solution
 of two pure states (the Helstrom bound), and then replace the normalized
 quantities with the original expressions: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\tilde{P}_{E} & =\frac{1}{2}[1-\sqrt{1-4\tilde{\eta}_{1}\tilde{\eta}_{2}\tilde{\omega}^{2}}],\nonumber \\
P_{E} & =\frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}}].\label{eq:optimize P_e}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is now one last optimization.
 Given a fixed rate of the average of inconclusive outcomes, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q,$
\end_inset

 what are the individual failure rates 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}.$
\end_inset

 To minimize Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:optimize P_e"

\end_inset

) we maximize the square root term 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}},$
\end_inset

 which in turn means to minimize 
\begin_inset Formula $(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}=(s^{2}+q_{1}q_{2}-2s\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}).$
\end_inset

 The overlap term 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2}$
\end_inset

 is fixed and we are left with 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}q_{2}-2s\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}.}$
\end_inset

 Only one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}'s$
\end_inset

 is an independent variable as we fix the overall failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2},$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Theta & = & q_{1}q_{2}-2s\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}.}\\
\Theta & = & \frac{q_{1}(Q_{0}-\eta_{1}q_{1}^{2})}{\eta_{2}}-2s\sqrt{\frac{q_{1}(Q_{0}-\eta_{1}q_{1}^{2})}{\eta_{2}}}\\
\Theta & = & \frac{\eta_{1}q_{1}Q_{0}-\eta_{1}^{2}q_{1}^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-2s\sqrt{\frac{\eta_{1}q_{1}Q_{0}-\eta_{1}^{2}q_{1}^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}}\\
\Theta & = & \frac{\tilde{q}_{1}Q_{0}-\tilde{q}_{1}^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-2s\sqrt{\frac{\tilde{q}_{1}Q_{0}-\tilde{q}_{1}^{2})}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q_{1}=\tilde{q}.$
\end_inset

 Let's optimize with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}_{1}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=\frac{\partial\Theta}{\partial\tilde{q}_{1}}=\frac{Q_{0}-2\tilde{q}_{1}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-2s\sqrt{\frac{Q_{0}-2\tilde{q}_{1}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
this leads to the optimality condition 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}=2\tilde{q}_{1}=2\eta_{1}q_{1}=2\eta_{2}q_{2},$
\end_inset

 giving the minimal error rate in discriminating two pure states with a
 fixed rate of failure as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}].\label{eq:frio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}=2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s$
\end_inset

 is the failure rate in the optimal unambiguous state discrimination, which
 our expression reaches when we set 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=0$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand when the failure rate is zero we can recover the Helstrom
 bound for two pure states 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}[1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}].$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Lagrange Multipliers Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the above method gives a closed form solution of the average error
 rate in terms of a FRIO it does not produce individual error or success
 rates, i.e the error rates of mistaking state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 for state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{j}\rangle$
\end_inset

 , which are needed for the implementation in calculating the transmittance
 and reflection coefficients of the beam splitters.
 To obtain these expressions we show another solution to the interpolation
 using the Lagrange multipliers method with the constraint in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general constraint"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to minimize the average error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}$
\end_inset

 subject to the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\sqrt{(1-r_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}}+\sqrt{(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}}+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}},$
\end_inset

 setting up the function with one Lagrange multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}+\lambda(s-\sqrt{(1-r_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}}-\sqrt{(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}}-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Setting the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $dF_{(r_{1},r_{2},\lambda)}/dr_{i}$
\end_inset

 to zero then solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

, we exploit the symmetry in the resulting equations to solve for the individual
 error rates 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the failure rates 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Subsequent substitution into the constraint gives us the optimal value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can obtain the total minimum error by replacing the expressions
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

 and minimizing 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

 under the additional constraint that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}=Q$
\end_inset

.
 This gives us the optimal relationship between failure rates as 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q_{1}=\eta_{2}q_{2}$
\end_inset

 and the total optimal error rate as 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=2\eta_{1}q_{1}=2\eta_{2}q_{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $dF/dr_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 and re-arranging we get: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(2\eta_{1}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{1}-r_{1})r_{1}}=\sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})(1-q_{1}-r_{1})}-\sqrt{r_{1}r_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $dF/dr_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(2\eta_{2}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})r_{2}}=\sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})(1-q_{1}-r_{1})}-\sqrt{r_{1}r_{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This step is algebraically challenging and requires the insight that the
 resulting equations can each be separated into two expressions, left hand
 side depending on only 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 and the right hand sides are equivalent.
 Because both equations have the same multivariable expression, we can set
 the left hand sides equal to a constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $C,$
\end_inset

 which is yet to be determined.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(2\eta_{1}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{1}-r_{1})r_{1}}=(2\eta_{2}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})r_{2}}\equiv C.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This greatly simplifies the problem, turning it into a quadratic equation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(2\eta_{i}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{i}-r_{i})r_{i}}=C.\label{eq:C}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}\equiv1-q_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sqrt{(\alpha_{1}-r_{i})r_{i}} & = & (\lambda C)/(2\eta_{i}),\\
r_{i}^{2}-\alpha_{i}r_{i}+\lambda^{2}C^{2}/4\eta_{i}^{2} & = & 0,\\
r_{i}(\pm) & = & 1/2\left(\alpha_{i}\pm\sqrt{\alpha_{i}^{2}-\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}}}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the error rate which we want to be minimized, thus we take the smaller
 root 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}(-).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{1} & = & 1/2\left(\alpha_{1}-\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{1}^{2}}}\right)=1/2\left(\alpha_{1}-A_{1}\right),\label{eq:r1(lambda)}\\
r_{2} & = & 1/2\left(\alpha_{2}-\sqrt{\alpha_{2}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{2}^{2}}}\right)=1/2\left(\alpha_{2}-A_{2}\right),\label{eq:r2(lambda)}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\equiv\lambda^{2}C^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}\equiv\sqrt{\alpha_{i}^{2}-(\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}})}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Insert the expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r1(lambda)"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r2(lambda)"

\end_inset

) into the constraint from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general constraint"

\end_inset

).
 First let us rewrite the constraint so it simplifies the algebra later:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega=(1-r_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}+(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}+\sqrt{(1-r_{1}-q_{1})(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}r_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\equiv(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We use the definition in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:C"

\end_inset

) to reduce the square root term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{(1-r_{1}-q_{1})(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}r_{2}}=\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}},$
\end_inset

 giving
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}=(1-r_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}+(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}+\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}=1-q_{i},$
\end_inset

 the above expression becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\omega & = & (\alpha_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}+(\alpha_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}+\frac{\delta}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}\\
 & = & \alpha_{1}r_{2}-\alpha_{2}r_{1}-2r_{1}r_{2}+\frac{\delta}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}\\
 & = & \frac{\alpha_{1}}{2}\left(\alpha_{2}-A_{2}\right)+\frac{\alpha_{2}}{2}\left(\alpha_{1}-A_{1}\right)-\frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha_{1}-A_{1}\right)\left(\alpha_{2}-A_{2}\right)+\frac{\delta}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}\\
 & = & \alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}-A_{1}A_{2}+\frac{\delta}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 by their respective value
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\omega & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}-\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{1}^{2}}}\sqrt{\alpha_{2}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{2}^{2}}}+\delta/\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\right],\\
\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{1}^{2}}}\sqrt{\alpha_{2}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{2}^{2}}} & = & \alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}+\delta/\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-2\omega.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Squaring both sides, using 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\alpha_{1}}{\eta_{2}}+\frac{\alpha_{2}}{\eta_{1}}=\frac{\alpha_{1}\eta_{1}+\alpha_{2}\eta_{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}=\frac{\eta_{1}(1-q_{1})+\eta_{2}(1-q_{2})}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}=\frac{1-Q}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}$
\end_inset

 and after some trivial algebra we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\delta\left[\frac{4\omega}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-\left(\frac{\alpha_{1}}{\eta_{2}}+\frac{\alpha_{2}}{\eta_{1}}\right)\right] & = & 4\omega^{2}-4\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2},\nonumber \\
\delta\left[\frac{4\omega}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-\frac{(1-Q)^{2}}{\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}\right] & = & 4\omega^{2}-4\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2},\nonumber \\
\delta & = & \frac{\left(\omega^{2}-\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}\right)4\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}{4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Now substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r1(lambda)"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{1} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha_{1}-\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{\eta_{1}^{2}}}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha_{1}-\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-\frac{1}{\eta_{1}^{2}}\frac{(\omega^{2}-\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2})4\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}{4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}}}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha_{1}-\sqrt{\frac{\alpha_{1}^{2}[4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}]-4\eta[\omega^{2}-\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}]}{4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}}}\right).
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The numerator can be greatly simplified:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}^{2}[4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}]-4\eta_{2}^{2}[\omega^{2}-\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}]=-\alpha_{1}^{2}(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{2}^{2}\omega^{2}+4\omega\eta_{2}\alpha_{1}[\eta_{1}\alpha_{1}+\eta_{2}\alpha_{2}]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=-[\alpha_{1}(1-Q)-2\eta_{2}\omega]^{2}=-[(1-q_{1})(1-Q)-2\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}]^{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The calculation for 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 goes along the same line.
 Expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 become:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{1} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[\left(1-q_{1}\right)-\frac{\left(1-q_{1}\right)\left(1-Q\right)-2\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}{\sqrt{(\left(1-Q\right))^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}}\right],\\
r_{2} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[\left(1-q_{2}\right)-\frac{\left(1-q_{2}\right)\left(1-Q\right)-2\eta_{1}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}{\sqrt{\left(1-Q\right)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}}\right].
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Finally 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 can be substituted into the overall average error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{E} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1-\left(\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}\right)-\frac{\left(1-Q\right)\left(\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}\right)-\left(\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}\right)-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}{\sqrt{\left(1-Q\right)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}}\right]\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[(1-Q)-\frac{\left(1-Q\right)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}{\sqrt{\left(1-Q\right)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}}\right]\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[(1-Q)-\sqrt{\left(1-Q\right)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}\right]\label{eq:P_E(q1,q2)}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has been showed in previous sections that (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:P_E(q1,q2)"

\end_inset

) is optimized for a fixed value of failure rate when 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q_{1}=\eta_{2}q_{2}.$
\end_inset

 Eq (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:P_E(q1,q2)"

\end_inset

) then reduces to the now well know FRIO form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}\left[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{0})^{2}}\right].
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The individual error and success rates can now be expressed explicitly in
 terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 and most importantly the fixed failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{i} & =\frac{1}{2}\left[\left(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}}\right)-\frac{\left(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}}\right)\left(1-Q\right)-\frac{1}{2\eta_{i}}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}}\right],\label{eq:r_i}\\
p_{i} & =\frac{1}{2}\left[\left(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}}\right)+\frac{\left(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}}\right)\left(1-Q\right)-\frac{1}{2\eta_{i}}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}}\right].\label{eq:p_i}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the first time that the individual error and failure rates have
 been calculated.
 An immediate application is that it can now be used in the calculations
 of the coefficients beam splitters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Choosing the physical implementation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main reason to seek a solution using the Neumark setup is because it
 lends itself to an optical implementation.
 This implementation, as we will see, can be carried out using only linear
 optical elements (beam splitters and a mirror).
 The possible states are represented by single photons and a photodetector
 will carry out the measurement process at the output.
 To choose the basis we start with the two mode vacuum state 
\begin_inset Formula $|00\rangle.$
\end_inset

 The total number of photons in both modes is one.
 This two dimensional Hilbert space where our photons live can be spanned
 by the states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|10\rangle,|01\rangle\}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $|10\rangle=a_{1}^{\dagger}|00\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|01\rangle=a_{2}^{\dagger}|00\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 are creation operators corresponding to two different modes of the electromagne
tic field.
 The basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|10\rangle,|01\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the basis of qubit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|0\rangle,|1\rangle\}.$
\end_inset

 The most general input state can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle=\alpha_{i}|0\rangle+\beta_{i}|1\rangle=\alpha_{i}|10\rangle+\beta_{i}|01\rangle$
\end_inset

 which can be produced by sending a photon into a beam splitter with some
 transmission and reflection coefficient, where the modes 1 and 2 correspond
 to the output modes of the beam splitter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A general 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

 port is a linear device with 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 input and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 output ports.
 It can be constructed from beam splitters and mirrors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bergou2009"

\end_inset

.
 For our work we will need a six-port, three input ports and three output
 ports.
 Let us denote the annihilation operators corresponding to the input modes
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j\text{\thinspace in }},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 then the output operators are given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{j\text{\thinspace out }}=U^{-1}a_{i\text{\thinspace in }}U=\sum M_{jk}a_{k\text{\thinspace in }},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{jk}$
\end_inset

 are the elements of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N$
\end_inset

 unitary matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M.$
\end_inset

 In the Schrodinger picture, the 
\begin_inset Formula $in$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $out$
\end_inset

 states are related by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{\psi}_{out}=U\ket{\psi}_{in}.
\]

\end_inset

 In general an 
\begin_inset Formula $in$
\end_inset

 state that contains a single photon can be described by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{\psi}_{in}=\sum_{j=1}^{3}c_{j}a_{j}^{\dagger}\ket{000},
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=1}^{3}\left|c_{j}\right|=1.$
\end_inset

 The output state is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket{\psi}_{in} & = & U\sum_{j=1}^{3}c_{j}a_{j}^{\dagger}U^{-1}\ket{000}\\
 & = & \sum_{j,k=1}^{3}c_{j}M_{jk}^{T}a_{j}^{\dagger}\ket{000},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we have made use of the fact that the vacuum is invariant under the
 transformation, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 To simplify the notation in the implementation section let:
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{100}\equiv\ket 1,\thinspace\ket{010}\equiv\ket 2,\thinspace\ket{001}\equiv\ket 3.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Implementation: equal priors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will first show the implementation of FRIO for equal priors.
 The Neumark in direct sum notation setup will be used to calculate the
 unitary matrix.
 The two input states to be discriminated can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle_{in}=|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle_{in}=\cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|2\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|1\rangle & = & \sqrt{p}|1\rangle+\sqrt{r}|2\rangle+\sqrt{q}|3\rangle,\label{eq:eq1}\\
U(\cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|2\rangle) & = & \sqrt{r}|1\rangle+\sqrt{p}|2\rangle+\sqrt{q}|3\rangle,\label{eq:eq2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the error and success rate was calculated in section 4.1.1: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}\right],\label{eq:r}\\
p & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[(1-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}\right],\label{eq:p}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the Neumark setup we can read out six out of nine elements of the unitary
 matrix.
 Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eq1"

\end_inset

) gives the first column, Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eq2"

\end_inset

) gives the second column and the last column can be constructed from the
 conditions of unitarity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get first column, multiply Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eq1"

\end_inset

) from the left with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 1,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 3:$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle1|U|1\rangle=U_{11}=\sqrt{p},
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle2|U|1\rangle=U_{21}=\sqrt{q},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle3|U|1\rangle=U_{31}=\sqrt{r}.
\]

\end_inset

To get the second column, multiply 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eq2"

\end_inset

 from the left with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 1,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 3:$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cos\theta\langle1|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle1|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{11}+\sin\theta U_{12}=\sqrt{r},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cos\theta\langle2|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle2|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{21}+\sin\theta U_{22}=\sqrt{p},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cos\theta\langle3|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle3|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{31}+\sin\theta U_{32}=\sqrt{q}.
\]

\end_inset

 Using the solution of the first column 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i1}$
\end_inset

, gives the entries to second column 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i2}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3),$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{p}_{1}+\sin\theta U_{12}=\sqrt{r_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{12}=\frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{q_{1}}+\sin\theta U_{22}=\sqrt{p_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{22}=\frac{[\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}]}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{r_{1}}+\sin\theta U_{32}=\sqrt{q_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{32}=\sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}}$
\end_inset

 ,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta=Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\theta=\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remaining elements be calculated from the conditions of the unitarity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{T}U=I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i1}^{2}+U_{i2}^{2}+U_{i3}^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{13}=\pm\sqrt{1-U_{11}^{2}-U_{12}^{2}}=\pm\sqrt{1-p-\frac{r+pQ_{o}^{2}-2\sqrt{pr}Q_{0}}{1-Q_{0}^{2}}}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{Q-Q_{o}^{2}+2\sqrt{pr}Q_{0}}{1-Q_{0}^{2}}}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{Q}{1-Q_{0}}}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{pr}=\frac{1}{2}(Q_{o}-Q)$
\end_inset

 was used, which is derived from the multiplication of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:p"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{23}=\pm\sqrt{1-U_{21}^{2}-U_{22}^{2}}=\pm\sqrt{1-r-\frac{p+rQ_{o}^{2}-2\sqrt{pr}Q_{0}}{1-Q_{0}^{2}}}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{Q}{1-Q_{0}}}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{33}=\pm\sqrt{1-U_{31}^{2}-U_{32}^{2}}=\pm\sqrt{1-Q-\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{1+Q_{o}}}=\pm\frac{\sqrt{p}+\sqrt{r}}{\sqrt{1+Q_{o}}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to notice the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{(1+Q_{o}-2Q)}=\sqrt{p}+\sqrt{r}$
\end_inset

 which is somewhat unexpected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full unitary, with the signs of the last column elements chosen so that
 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{13}^{2}+U_{23}^{2}+U_{33}^{2}=1,$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & \frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{r} & \frac{\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{Q} & \sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}} & \frac{\sqrt{p}+\sqrt{r}}{\sqrt{1+Q_{o}}}
\end{pmatrix}.\label{eq:U(equal prior)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In this representation the above matrix can be shown that it satisfies all
 the unitary conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unitary in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U(equal prior)"

\end_inset

) interpolates between the optimal ME and UD schemes varying the fixed rate
 of inconclusive results 
\begin_inset Formula $Q.$
\end_inset

 Setting the failure rate to zero, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0,$
\end_inset

 collapses it into the unitary of optimal ME:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{ME}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & \frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & 0\\
\sqrt{r} & \frac{\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
which can be simplified further by noticing 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{12})^{2}=\left(\frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}}\right)^{2}=r,$
\end_inset

 similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{22})^{2}=\left(\frac{\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}}\right)^{2}=p$
\end_inset

, simplifying the unitary into: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{ME}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & \sqrt{r} & 0\\
\sqrt{r} & -\sqrt{p} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

only one beam splitter in needed for optimal ME measurements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand setting the error rate of the unitary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U(equal prior)"

\end_inset

 to zero gives the optimal UD unitary,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{UD}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & -\frac{\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q_{0}}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
0 & \frac{\sqrt{p}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q_{o}}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{Q_{0}} & \sqrt{\frac{Q_{o}(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}} & \sqrt{\frac{1-Q_{o}}{1+Q_{o}}}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All three beamsplitters are still necessary for a general UD measurement.
 This is because the measurement is essentially two-step: in the first step
 the states are made orthogonal, then upon succeeding a projective measurement
 is performed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now express the interpolating unitary in terms of three beamsplitters,
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $U=M_{1}M_{2}M_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This ordering was derived using the Reck-Zeilinger algorithm which says
 that any discreet finite unitary matrix can be expressed in terms of beamsplitt
ers and phase shifters.
 The beamsplitters can be written in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and it is easy to check the unitarity condition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin^{2}\omega_{i}+\cos^{2}\omega_{i}=1.$
\end_inset

 Then the task is that of calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}\sin\omega & \cos\omega_{1} & 0\\
\cos\omega & -\sin\omega & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}\sin\omega_{2} & 0 & \cos\omega_{2}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
\cos\omega_{2} & 0 & -\sin\omega_{2}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \sin\omega_{3} & \cos\omega_{3}\\
0 & \cos\omega_{3} & -\sin\omega_{3}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=M_{1}M_{2}M_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & \frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & \sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{r} & \frac{[\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}]}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & \sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{Q} & \sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}} & \sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{1+Q_{o}}}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\begin{pmatrix}\sin\omega_{1}\sin\omega_{2} & \cos\omega_{1}\sin\omega_{3}+\sin\omega_{1}\cos\omega_{2}\cos\omega_{3} & \cos\omega_{1}\cos\omega_{3}-\sin\omega_{1}\cos\omega_{2}\sin\omega_{3}\\
\cos\omega_{1}\sin\omega_{2} & -\sin\omega_{1}\sin\omega_{3}+\cos\omega_{1}\cos\omega_{2}\cos\omega_{3} & -\sin\omega_{1}\cos\omega_{3}-\cos\omega_{1}\cos\omega_{2}\sin\omega_{3}\\
\cos\omega_{2} & -\sin\omega_{2}\cos\omega_{3} & \sin\omega_{2}\sin\omega_{3}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives nine equations and only three independent variables to be calculated.
 All the elements can be obtained by using just 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{31},U_{32},U_{21}:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{2}=U_{31}=\sqrt{Q},\sin\omega_{2}=\sqrt{1-r^{2}}=\sqrt{1-Q}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{3}=-\sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{(1+Q_{o})(1-Q)}},\sin\omega_{3}=\sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{(1-Q)(1+Q_{o})}}=\frac{\sqrt{p}+\sqrt{r}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)(1+Q_{o})}}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{r}{1-Q}},\sin\omega_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{p}{1-Q}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The three beamsplitters with the proper coefficients of reflectivity and
 transmittance are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{\frac{p}{1-Q}} & \sqrt{\frac{r}{1-Q}} & 0\\
\sqrt{\frac{r}{1-Q}} & -\sqrt{\frac{p}{1-Q}} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{1-Q} & 0 & \sqrt{Q}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
\sqrt{Q} & 0 & -\sqrt{1-Q}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{(1-Q)(1+Q_{o})}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{(1+Q_{o})(1-Q)}}\\
0 & -\sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{(1+Q_{o})(1-Q)}} & -\sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{(1-Q)(1+Q_{o})}}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By choosing the FRIO this matrix minimizes the error rate and maximizes
 the rate of success.
 Hence, by setting the FRIO to zero we obtain the setup to the minimum error
 problem.
 On the other hand, setting the error rate to zero gives the setup of the
 optimal unambiguous discrimination where the optimal inconclusive rate
 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}=s$
\end_inset

.
 This simplifies the works of the experimentalists because now they only
 need one setup and are not restrained to the extreme points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Implementation: Unequal priors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we derive the beamsplitter coefficients necessary to interpolate
 minimum error measurements with a 
\begin_inset Formula $FRIO$
\end_inset

 when the input states are prepared with different a priori probabilities.
 The two input states to be discriminated are 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle_{in}=|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle_{in}=\cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|2\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 A unitary operator carries out the operation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U|1\rangle & =\sqrt{p_{1}}|1\rangle+\sqrt{r_{1}}|2\rangle+\sqrt{q_{1}}|3\rangle,\label{eq:U1}\\
U(\cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|2\rangle) & =\sqrt{r_{2}}|1\rangle+\sqrt{p_{2}}|2\rangle+\sqrt{q_{2}}|3\rangle.\label{eq:U2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The error and success rates where calculated in Section 4.1.4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{i} & =\frac{1}{2}\left[(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}})-\frac{(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}})(1-Q)-\frac{1}{2\eta_{i}}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}}\right],\\
p_{i} & =\frac{1}{2}\left[(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}})+\frac{(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}})(1-Q)-\frac{1}{2\eta_{i}}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}}\right].
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the two equation in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U1"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U2"

\end_inset

) we can read out six of nine elements of the three by three unitary matrix.
 Multiplying (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U1"

\end_inset

) on the left hand side by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\langle1|,\bra 2,\bra 3\}$
\end_inset

 will give the elements 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i1},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3.$
\end_inset

 Similarly we can obtain three more elements for the second column.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first column is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\langle1|U|1\rangle=U_{11}=\sqrt{p_{1}},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\langle2|U|1\rangle=U_{21}=\sqrt{q_{1}},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\langle3|U|1\rangle=U_{31}=\sqrt{r_{1}}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second Column:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\langle1|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle1|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{11}+\sin\theta U_{12}=\sqrt{r_{2}},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\langle2|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle2|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{21}+\sin\theta U_{22}=\sqrt{p_{2}},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\langle3|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle3|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{31}+\sin\theta U_{32}=\sqrt{q_{2}}$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the solution of the first column 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i1}$
\end_inset

, gives the explicit entries to second column 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i2}:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{p}_{1}+\sin\theta U_{12}=\sqrt{r_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{12}=\frac{\sqrt{r_{2}}-\sqrt{p_{1}}\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{q_{1}}+\sin\theta U_{22}=\sqrt{p_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{22}=\frac{\sqrt{p_{2}}-\sqrt{r_{1}}\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{r_{1}}+\sin\theta U_{32}=\sqrt{q_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{32}=\frac{\sqrt{q_{2}}-\sqrt{q_{1}}\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last column be calculated from the conditions of the unitarity, 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{T}U=I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i1}^{2}+U_{i2}^{2}+U_{i3}^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{13}=\pm\sqrt{1-U_{11}^{2}-U_{12}^{2}}=\pm\sqrt{1-p_{1}-\frac{r_{2}+p_{1}\cos\theta-2\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}\cos\theta}{\sin^{2}\theta}}=\pm\frac{\sqrt{\sin^{2}\theta-p_{1}-r_{2}+2\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}\cos\theta}}{\sin\theta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{23}=\pm\frac{\sqrt{\sin^{2}\theta-r_{1}-p_{2}+2\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}\cos\theta}}{\sin\theta},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{33}=\pm\frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-q_{1}-q_{2}+2\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\cos\theta}}{\sin\theta}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that all the elements have been calculated the unitary is: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p_{1}} & \frac{\sqrt{r_{2}}-\sqrt{p_{1}}\cos\theta}{\sin\theta} & -\frac{\sqrt{\sin^{2}\theta-p_{1}-r_{2}+2\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}\cos\theta}}{\sin\theta}\\
\sqrt{r_{1}} & \frac{\sqrt{p_{2}}-\sqrt{r_{1}}\cos\theta}{\sin\theta} & -\frac{\sqrt{\sin^{2}\theta-r_{1}-p_{2}+2\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}\cos\theta}}{\sin\theta}\\
\sqrt{q_{1}} & \frac{\sqrt{q_{2}}-\sqrt{q_{1}}\cos\theta}{\sin\theta} & +\frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-q_{1}-q_{2}+2\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\cos\theta}}{\sin\theta}
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth mentioning that all equations in this section referencing 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 are using the optimal values (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r_i"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:p_i"

\end_inset

) derived in the previous section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have a full unitary matrix we want to express it in terms of
 linear optical devices.
 Again the Reck-Zeilinger algorithm is used to decompose the unitary in
 terms of beamsplitters and their ordering 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sixport"

\end_inset

.
 The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is decomposed into beamsplitters in the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $U=M_{1}\cdot M_{2}\cdot M_{3}$
\end_inset

, and no phase shifters are needed: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M_{1} & =\begin{pmatrix}\sin\omega_{1} & \cos\omega_{1} & 0\\
\cos\omega_{1} & -\sin\omega_{1} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},\\
M_{2} & =\begin{pmatrix}\sin\omega_{2} & 0 & \cos\omega_{2}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
\cos\omega_{2} & 0 & -\sin\omega_{2}
\end{pmatrix},\\
M_{3} & =\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \sin\omega_{3} & \cos\omega_{3}\\
0 & \cos\omega_{3} & -\sin\omega_{3}
\end{pmatrix},\\
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename BeamSplitters.png
	width 8.5cm
	height 8.5cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space \hspace{}
\length 1cm
\end_inset

Six port interferometer
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sixport"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

where the coefficients of reflectivity and transmittance are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{R_{i}}=\sin\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{T_{i}}=\cos\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U=M_{1}M_{2}M_{3}$
\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
=
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p_{1}} & \frac{\sqrt{r_{2}}-\sqrt{p_{1}}cos\theta}{sin\theta} & \pm\frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-p_{1}-r_{2}+2\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}cos\theta}}{sin^{2}\theta}\\
\sqrt{r_{1}} & \frac{\sqrt{p_{2}}-\sqrt{r_{1}}cos\theta}{sin\theta} & \pm\frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-r_{1}-p_{2}+2\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}cos\theta}}{sin^{2}\theta}\\
\sqrt{q_{1}} & \frac{\sqrt{q_{2}}-\sqrt{q_{1}}cos\theta}{sin\theta} & \pm\frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-q_{1}-q_{2}+2\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}cos\theta}}{sin^{2}\theta}
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=\begin{pmatrix}sin\omega_{1}sin\omega_{2} & cos\omega_{1}sin\omega_{3}+sin\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}cos\omega_{3} & cos\omega_{1}cos\omega_{3}-sin\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}sin\omega_{3}\\
cos\omega_{1}sin\omega_{2} & -sin\omega_{1}sin\omega_{3}+cos\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}cos\omega_{3} & -sin\omega_{1}cos\omega_{3}-cos\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}sin\omega_{3}\\
cos\omega_{2} & -sin\omega_{2}cos\omega_{3} & sin\omega_{2}sin\omega_{3}
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coefficients of reflectivity and transmittance can be calculated by
 matching the corresponding elements of the unitary and it's decomposition.
 We can get all the elements by using just 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{31},U_{32}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{33}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{31}=\sqrt{q_{1}}=\cos\omega_{2},\sin\omega_{2}=\sqrt{1-\cos\omega_{2}^{2}}=\sqrt{1-q_{1}}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{32}=\frac{\sqrt{q_{2}}-\sqrt{q_{1}}cos\theta}{sin\theta}=-\sin\omega_{2}\cos\omega_{3}=-\sqrt{1-q_{1}}\cos\omega_{3}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{3}=-\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-q_{1}}}[\frac{\sqrt{q_{2}}-\sqrt{q_{1}}cos\theta}{sin\theta}],$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\omega_{3}=\sqrt{1-\cos\omega_{3}}=-\frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-q_{1}-q_{2}+2\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}cos\theta}}{\sqrt{1-q_{1}}sin\theta},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{21}=\sqrt{r_{1}}=\cos\omega_{1}\sin\omega_{2}=\cos\omega_{1}\sqrt{1-q_{1}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-q_{1}}},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\omega_{1}=\sqrt{1-\cos\omega_{1}}=\sqrt{\frac{p_{1}}{1-q_{1}}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the coefficients of reflectivity and transmittance the beamsplitter
s are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{\frac{p_{1}}{1-q_{1}}} & \sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-q_{1}}} & 0\\
\sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-q_{1}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{p_{1}}{1-q_{1}}} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},\,M_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{1-q_{1}} & 0 & \sqrt{q_{1}}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
\sqrt{q_{1}} & 0 & -\sqrt{1-q_{1}}
\end{pmatrix},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-q_{1}-q_{2}+2\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}cos\theta}}{\sqrt{1-q_{1}}sin\theta} & -\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-q_{1}}}[\frac{\sqrt{q_{2}}-\sqrt{q_{1}}cos\theta}{sin\theta}]\\
0 & -\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-q_{1}}}[\frac{\sqrt{q_{2}}-\sqrt{q_{1}}cos\theta}{sin\theta}] & -\frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-q_{1}-q_{2}+2\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}cos\theta}}{\sqrt{1-q_{1}}sin\theta}
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the coefficients can be expressed in terms of the 
\begin_inset Formula $FRIO$
\end_inset

.
 Using the optimal relationship between the individual failure rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q_{1}=\eta_{2}q_{2}=Q/2$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\thinspace q_{1}=Q/2\eta_{1},\thinspace q_{2}=Q/2\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 and the above expressions of success and error rates.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\omega_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{p_{1}}{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{2}=\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{1}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\omega_{2}=\sqrt{1-Q/2\eta_{1}},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{3}=-\frac{\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{2}}-Q_{o}/2\eta_{1}\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{2}}}{\sqrt{(1-Q/2\eta_{1})(1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\omega_{3}=\frac{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-Q/(2\eta_{1}\eta_{2})+QQ_{o}/(2\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}}{\sqrt{(1-Q/2\eta_{1})(1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{\frac{p_{1}}{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}} & \sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}} & 0\\
\sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{p_{1}}{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{1-Q/2\eta_{1}} & 0 & \sqrt{Q/2\eta_{1}}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{1}} & 0 & -\sqrt{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \frac{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-Q/(2\eta_{1}\eta_{2})+QQ_{o}/(2\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}}{\sqrt{(1-Q/2\eta_{1})(1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}} & -\frac{\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{2}}-Q_{o}/2\eta_{1}\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{2}}}{\sqrt{(1-Q/2\eta_{1})(1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}}\\
0 & -\frac{\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{2}}-Q_{o}/2\eta_{1}\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{2}}}{\sqrt{(1-Q/2\eta_{1})(1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}} & -\frac{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-Q/(2\eta_{1}\eta_{2})+QQ_{o}/(2\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}}{\sqrt{(1-Q/2\eta_{1})(1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace 0.05in
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now check the bounds of the general unitary matrix for equal priors
 to see if it reproduces the unitary in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U(equal prior)"

\end_inset

).
 Indeed, everything checks out and the equal priors unitary matrix is reproduced
: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & \frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & \sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{r} & \frac{[\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}]}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & \sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{Q} & \sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}} & -\frac{\sqrt{p}+\sqrt{r}}{\sqrt{1+Q_{o}}}
\end{pmatrix},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary in this chapter we have shown that two nonorthogonal quantum
 states, each realized as a photon split between two modes, in combination
 with a six-port interferometer can be used to implement state discrimination
 with FRIO.
 The implementation requires only optical elements: beam splitters and mirrors.
 All the proper coefficients of transmittance and reflectivity were calculated
 and we believe it should be possible to construct the setup in a laboratory.
 The setup should give the experimentalist more freedom when designing a
 quantum computation network as now only one setup is needed to perform
 UD, ME and interpolate with a fixed rate of inconclusive results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter*
Appendix 1: Reck-Zeilinger Algorithm 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimizing the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 we differentiate with respect to all the independent variables 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 and follow the procedure defined above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In their letter 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reck1994"

\end_inset

 prove that any discrete finite-dimensional unitary operator can be constructed
 using optical devices only.
 Then they provide a general algorithm which decomposes any 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 unitary matrix into a product of two-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $U(2)$
\end_inset

 transformations which can be expressed as beam splitters, phase shifters
 and mirrors.
 This optical multi-port can act upon various fields such as electrons,
 neutrons, atoms, photons etc.
 The authors decide to work with photons purely for convenience and widespread
 availability of high power lasers.
 It is this very proof which allows us to implement our various works in
 state discrimination and cloning.
 In addition the proof has greatly simplified the experimental realizations
 of many quantum computation, quantum information and quantum cryptography
 schemes.
 Besides these very practical applications it has also answered a long standing
 question: Does an experiment measuring the variables corresponding to any
 arbitrary Hermitian operator exists? They show that indeed an experimental
 realization does exist for an arbitrary operator in a finite dimensional
 Hilbert space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has long been known that a lossless beam splitter and a phase shifter
 can implement any 
\begin_inset Formula $U(2)$
\end_inset

 transformation: a beam splitter and a phase shifter at one output port
 transforms the input operators into output operators as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{pmatrix}a'_{1}\\
a'_{2}
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}e^{i\phi}\sin\omega & e^{i\phi}\cos\omega\\
\cos\omega & -\sin\omega
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}\\
a_{2}
\end{pmatrix},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the phase shifter which can be realized as an external phase shifter
 after the beam splitter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 represents the transmittance and reflectivity coefficient, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{T}=\cos\omega,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{R}=\sin\omega.$
\end_inset

 In their Letter, Reck 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al.$
\end_inset

 considered the use of a Mach-Zehner interferometer to simulate the effect
 of a beam splitter which splits the incoming beam according to the given
 parameters of transmittance and reflectivity.
 For an actual two by two beam splitter the coefficients of transmittance
 and reflectivity should be 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{T}=\sin\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{R}=\sin\theta.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The authors show that starting with an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 unitary matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $U(N),$
\end_inset

 it can be expressed into a succession of two-dimensional matrices which
 correspond to beam splitters and phase shifters.
 Hence the 
\begin_inset Formula $U(N)$
\end_inset

 unitary matrix can be realized in the full 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 dimensional Hilbert space through a succession of two-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $U(2)$
\end_inset

 matrices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The order in which the matrices are multiplied correspond to the sequence
 in which the beamsplitters are set up.
 The task of realizing the experimental setup of an arbitrary unitary matrix
 becomes that of factorizing the matrix in terms of two dimensional beam
 splitter matrices with phase shifters which can be placed after the beam
 splitters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define an 
\begin_inset Formula $N-$
\end_inset

dimensional identity matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{pq}$
\end_inset

 which multiplies the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 dimensional unitary matrix from the right to reduce the dimensionality
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $N-1.$
\end_inset

 In the identity matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{pq}$
\end_inset

 the elements 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{pq},\;I_{pp},\;I_{qp},\;I_{qq}$
\end_inset

 are replaced by the corresponding beam splitter matrix elements 
\begin_inset Formula $(\cos\omega,\sin\omega)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(N)\times T_{N,N-1}\times T_{N,N-2}\times...T_{N,1}=\begin{pmatrix}U(N-1) & 0\\
0 & e^{i\phi}
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This reduces the dimensionality of 
\begin_inset Formula $U(N)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $U(N-1).$
\end_inset

 The process is repeated again until all the off diagonal elements of the
 original unitary matrix are zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(N)\cdot T_{N,N-1}\cdot T_{N,N-2}\cdot...T_{N,1}\cdot T_{N-1,N-2}\cdot T_{N-2,N-2}\cdot...T_{2,1}\cdot...T_{2,1}=\begin{pmatrix}e^{i\alpha_{1}} & 0 & .. & 0\\
\vdots & e^{i\alpha_{2}}\\
 &  & \ddots\\
0 & \cdots &  & e^{i\alpha N}
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=\begin{pmatrix}e^{-i\alpha_{1}} & 0 & .. & 0\\
\vdots & e^{-i\alpha_{2}}\\
 &  & \ddots\\
0 & \cdots &  & e^{-i\alpha N}
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(N)\cdot T_{N,N-1}\cdot T_{N,N-2}\cdot...T_{N,1}\cdot T_{N-1,N-2}\cdot T_{N-2,N-2}\cdot...T_{2,1}\cdot D=I
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The unitary matrix can be expressed in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $Tp,q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(N)=D^{-1}\cdot T_{2,1}....\cdot T_{N-2,N-2}^{-1}\cdot T_{N-1,N-2}^{-1}\cdot T_{N,1}^{-1}....\cdot T_{N,N-2}^{-1}\cdot T_{N,N-1}^{-1}.\label{eq:reck-seilinger algorithm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Since the product of matrices represents the order in which the beam splitters
 are set up, then (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:reck-seilinger algorithm"

\end_inset

) is all one needs to implement a finite dimensional unitary matrix.
 Since this algorithm is recursive, it can factorize any finite dimensional
 unitary operator.
 For example a 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 unitary matrix, three beam splitters are needed 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{21},T_{31},T_{32},$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 unitary matrix requires six beamsplitters 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{4,3},T_{4,2},T_{4,1},T_{32},T_{31},T_{21}$
\end_inset

 in reversed order.
 In general the maximum number of beam splitters required for any 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 dimensional unitary operator is 
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{pmatrix}N\\
2
\end{pmatrix}=\frac{N(N-1)}{2}.$
\end_inset

 In practice this method involves a triangular array of beamsplitters (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "coherent"

\end_inset

), with each diagonal row effectively reducing the dimension of the Hilbert
 space by one.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
enter graphics, fig 3 of reck-zeilinger paper.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now give an example to see explicitly how this algorithm works.
 For a three dimensional unitary operator 
\begin_inset Formula $U(3),$
\end_inset

 the algorithm in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:reck-seilinger algorithm"

\end_inset

) gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(3)=D^{-1}\times T_{2,1}^{-1}\times T_{3,1}^{-1}\times T_{3,2}^{-1}\label{eq:U(3)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-1}=\begin{pmatrix}e^{i\alpha_{1}} & 0 & 0\\
0 & e^{i\alpha_{2}} & 0\\
0 & 0 & e^{i\alpha_{3}}
\end{pmatrix},\ T_{21}=\begin{pmatrix}\sin\omega_{1} & \cos\omega_{1} & 0\\
\cos\omega_{1} & -\sin\omega_{1} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $T_{31}=\begin{pmatrix}\sin\omega_{2} & 0 & \cos\omega_{2}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
\cos\omega_{2} & 0 & -\sin\omega_{2}
\end{pmatrix},\thinspace T_{32}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \sin\omega_{3} & \cos\omega_{3}\\
0 & \cos\omega_{3} & -\sin\omega_{3}
\end{pmatrix}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain the transmittance and reflective coefficients match the corresponding
 entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

 with the elements on right hand side multiplying the three beam splitter
 matrix with the phase shifter matrix.
 In the process nine equations and six independent unknowns are produced.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Enter graphics here from the reck-zeilinger paper for three beam splitters.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig1-coherent.jpg
	width 8.5cm
	height 8.5cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space \hspace{}
\length 1cm
\end_inset

NxN interferometer
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "coherent"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter*
Appendix 2: Lagrange Multipliers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our works we have relied quite heavily on the method of Lagrange multipliers
 when optimizing a function which was under the restriction of a constraint.
 We now show how it works 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Barnett2009"

\end_inset

.
 The method can be applied to a function of any number of variables but
 it can be more clearly explained in two variables.
 Suppose that we need to find the stationary points of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y),$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are the two variables, subject to the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,y)=0.$
\end_inset

 If the constraint is simple then we can solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $y,$
\end_inset

 plug it into the function and solve 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial f/\partial y=0.$
\end_inset

 However for a more complicated constraint this can easily lead to a very
 high order equation with cannot be solved analytically.
 In the case of exact cloning, doing just so leads to a sixth order equation
 which is of little use.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To find the stationary points of a function of two variables such as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y),$
\end_inset

 we could just take the total differential 
\begin_inset Formula $df$
\end_inset

 and set it to zero
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
df=\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}dx+\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}dy=0,\label{eq:lagrange 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which leads to two conditions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}=0,\ \ \frac{\partial f}{\partial y}=0.\label{eq:lagrange 0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However there is a constraint which means that the differentials 
\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dy$
\end_inset

 are not independent, they are related to the total differential of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dg=\frac{\partial g}{\partial x}dx+\frac{\partial g}{\partial y}dy=0.\label{eq:lagrange 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiplying (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange 2"

\end_inset

) by the Lagrange parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and adding it to (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange 1"

\end_inset

) we get 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d(f+\lambda g)=(\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}+\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial x})dx+(\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}+\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial y})dy
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation can be satisfied by choosing the Lagrange multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 such that the following two conditions are satisfied:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}+\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial x}=0\label{eq:lagrange x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}+\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial y}=0\label{eq:lagrange y}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get the stationary points of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset

 follow this procedure:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solve the two equations: (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange x"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange y"

\end_inset

) in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(\lambda)$
\end_inset

; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Plug 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 into the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,y)$
\end_inset

 ;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Plug the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(\lambda)$
\end_inset

; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Plug 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 into the function which was to be optimized 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have seen how the Lagrange multipliers method works, we can
 simplify the procedure by optimizing the function following function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F(x,y)=f(x,y)+\lambda g(x,y)\label{eq:lagrange full}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with respect to the the independent variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y.$
\end_inset

 Differentiating (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange full"

\end_inset

) with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y,$
\end_inset

 we obtain equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange x"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange y"

\end_inset

).
 The rest of the procedure is the same.
 This is the exact procedure we used for our works, for example in optimizing
 the error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}(r_{1},r_{2})$
\end_inset

 with one constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $s(r_{1},r_{2}).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset bibtex
LatexCommand bibtex
bibfiles "/Users/ashehu/Desktop/mendeley"
options "unsrt"

\end_inset


\end_layout

